<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Reported Visit of US Congressman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran has denied the report that
it agreed to a visit of U.S. Democrat congressman Tom Lantos to
Iran, the evening daily Etelaat reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry has never issued permission for
Lantos to visit Iran, the ministry's spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
was quoted as saying. But he did not say why.
</P>
<P>
Iran was reported to have agreed with Lantos' visit to the
country after the U.S. congressman expressed his interest in
visiting Iran following the address of Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami to the American people.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Lantos, a member of the House
International Relations Committee, sent a letter to Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami on Thursday when Khatami's interview
with the Cable News Network was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congressman intended to see whether there was a basis
for the United States and Iran to improve their strained
relations, after Khatami called for a people-to-people dialogue
instead of a government-to-government one, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Etelaat reported that Lantos' last visit to Iran happened in
1978, one year before the Islamic Revolution, which ousted the
late pro-American Shah's regime.
</P>
<P>
Washington and Tehran severed diplomatic ties in 1980 and
remained sworn enemies after Iranian students occupied the
American Embassy in Tehran and held its staff hostages for more
than one year.
</P>
<P>
However, secret contacts between the two governments continued
through the Swiss Embassy in Tehran, which takes care of American
interests in Iran. The latest contact was Washington's demand for
direct talks between the two governments earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats here noted that there are many hurdles for
the two countries to clear before they can take substantial steps
in improving relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
