<HEADLINE> U.S. Government to Fight Drug Use in Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to rid prisons
of drugs, the U.S. government may withhold federal funds from
state prisons that fail to report the extent of illegal drug use
among inmates, The New York Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The information the prisons provide is to be used to create a
baseline to measure their progress in reducing inmate drug use,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton was scheduled Monday to sign a
directive, a copy of which was obtained by the Times.
</P>
<P>
The document reflects the administration's belief that crimping
the supply of drugs in prison will cut the demand for them after
the convicts are released, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
"With more than half the individuals in our criminal justice
system estimated to have a substance abuse problem, promoting
coerced abstinence within the criminal justice system offers us a
unique opportunity to break the cycle of crime and drugs," the
document says.
</P>
<P>
A report last week by the National Center on Addiction and
Substance Abuse at Columbia University estimated that alcohol and
illegal drugs contributed to the incarceration of 80 percent of
the 1.7 million inmates in the nation's prisons. The report said
that the majority of them were not being treated for addiction
before being released.
</P>
<P>
The administration has increased to 42 from 32 the number of
drug treatment centers in federal prisons and more than tripled
the number of federal inmates undergoing substance abuse treatment
-- from 5,450 in 1993 to 19,943 in the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton plan also proposes that Attorney General Janet Reno
draft legislation allowing states to use federal money earmarked
for prison construction to test and treat prisoners and parolees
for drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
