<HEADLINE> Georgia Determined to Improve Relations With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Georgian leadership is
determined to resolve all disputes with Russia through
negotiations, Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze said today,
the Interfax news agency reported from Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
In his latest statement broadcast by the national radio,
Shevardnadze said there are several disputes over economic,
financial, border and other issues between Russia and all
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries, but these
problems should be resolved through fair negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Georgian-Russian military talks held last
week, Shevardnadze said that a lot of problems which emerged there
may take several years to be settled.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian president described the visit by a Russian
military delegation headed by chief of the Main Department of
International Military Cooperation Colonel-General Leonid Ivashov
to Georgia last week as "one more step forward" on the way of
solving the problems accumulated in Georgian-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze in the radio also explained his remark on January
2 that Georgia would not refuse to use the "Bosnian format" to
settle the regional conflicts in full accordance with the U.N.
Charter.
</P>
<P>
He once again said it would be expedient to apply such measures
on Abkhazia if the "Georgian-Abkhazian talks, which have lasted
for more than four years, fail to bring about any results."
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry on January 6 stated that Russia
does not agree to settle the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict by using
military forces and that military means could only deteriorate the
situation and lead to more bloodshed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
