<HEADLINE> U.S. to Back Baltic Membership in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
three Baltic nations will sign a formal charter later this week to
explicitly support efforts by Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania to
join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
However, in a report Sunday, the New York Times quoted U.S.
officials as saying that the document, called the Charter of
Partnership, does not promise membership, which is only decided by
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
The document will not pledge the U.S. to the defense of the
Baltic countries, but embody a moral and political commitment to
the independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
three countries.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of the three countries will join U.S. President
Bill Clinton on Friday in a White House signing ceremony, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The charter promised the Baltic nations that Washington will do
everything possible to get them ready to join NATO and support
their efforts to do so.
</P>
<P>
"For the Clinton Administration, this public display of
commitment will be the most formal demonstration to date that
America's plans for Europe's future are not limited to the first
round of NATO expansion," the New York Times said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has strongly protested the alliance's enlargement and
warned against any expansion into the Baltics.
</P>
<P>
Washington, however, insists that NATO's door is open to any
countries in Europe, including the Baltics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
