<HEADLINE> Germany: 200 Mln Marks for East European Holocaust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The German government today
announced that it would pay 200 million marks (110 million U.S.
dollars) in compensation for Holocaust survivors in eastern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Friedrich Bohl, head of Chancellor Helmut Kohl's office, said
in a statement that during the four-year period from 1999 to 2002,
Bonn would each year provide 50 million marks (28 million dollars)
for a special foundation run by the Jewish Claims Conference (JCC)
to help survivors.
</P>
<P>
Bohl worked out the concrete terms with the JCC last week,
which is a New York-based body founded in 1951 to represent Jewish
claimants living outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
The JCC and the foundation will decide on how to disburse the
aid to the Holocaust survivors in eastern Europe. However, only
about 18,000 people who had so far not yet received any personal
compensation from Germany are entitled to the aid.
</P>
<P>
According to Bohl, Bonn intended to continue with its own
separate projects for Nazi victims in eastern Europe, in which it
has since 1991 paid out a total of 1.8 billion marks (1.0 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Bonn has insisted on collective compensation in the form of
building hospitals or old age homes. Most of the Holocaust
survivors living in eastern Europe have never been individually
compensated by Bonn as those in the West.
</P>
<P>
Germany says it has paid out some 100 billion marks (55 billion
dollars) since World War II in compensation for crimes committed
during the Nazi rule from 1933 to 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
