<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siemens, Motorola Team UP in Chip Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's electronics giant
Siemens AG and its U.S. partner Motorola Inc. announced Monday a
joint venture agreement to develop a new computer chip-making
technology at the eastern German city of Dresden.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is aimed at developing new technology to
produce computer chips on 300-millimeter wafer boards, wider than
the current industry standard of 200 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Moving to larger wafers will allow the companies to produce
roughly 2.5 times more chips per wafer and to cut production costs
by about 30 percent, said Siemens chief executive Heinrich von
Pierer at a news conference in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Siemens-Motorola joint venture, which
would be the biggest microelectronics project ever started in
Europe, is expected to cost 1.5 billion marks (890 million
U.S. dollars), with the research and development costs alone
expected to exceed 1 billion marks (595 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The German government will also provide about 250 million marks
(150 million dollars) in state subsidies to support the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
