<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's New Motor Vehicle Sales Up in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian dealers sold 123,355
new motor vehicles in November, up 3.4 percent over October,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
That figure represents the largest number of new vehicles sold
in any month since January 1990, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
New passenger car sales rose 3.2 percent following two
consecutive monthly declines, while sales of new trucks rose 3.6
percent in November.
</P>
<P>
Compared with November 1996, Canada's new motor vehicle sales
jumped 15.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sales of new motor vehicles have been on the rise since
mid-1996. However, they remain below the levels reached in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In November, Canadian consumers bought 46.5 percent more
imported new motor vehicles than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
As a result, imported new motor vehicles claimed 12.7 percent
of Canadian sales, up from 10.0 percent in November 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
