<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Human Rights Reason for Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today reiterated that
the illegal Kurdish immigrants went to Europe not because of
fearing political prosecution, but due to economic reasons.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing here, Turkish Foreign
Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said that the Kurds who headed for
 Italy and other European nations were in pursuit of a better life
in rich Western countries.
</P>
<P>
It is groundless to hold that these illegal immigrants were
fleeing political prosecution, Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of illegal immigrants entered Italy by sea over
the past weeks, and some of them apparently tried to go to
Germany and other European countries from there.
</P>
<P>
Recent Western press reports said that the illegal immigrants,
mostly Kurds from Turkey and northern Iraq, rushed to Europe
since they feared they might suffer prosecution.
</P>
<P>
"It is a general tendency that people living in low-income
countries wish to go to rich Western countries," Utkan said,
adding that this kind of immigration is not a peculiar phenomenon
of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK), which has been fighting the Turkish government for
autonomy since 1984, also played a part in the illegal immigration
flood.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that other underground organizations,
including mafia, were also involved in this exodus.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Austria and other European countries had expressed
their grave concern over the issue, demanding that Turkey adopt
effective measures to halt this immigration flood.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they also called on Italy to take cautious steps in
dealing with these illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government was reportedly examining these illegal
immigrants and would granted some of them political asylum if
they were proved political refugees.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Interior Ministry is now organizing a nation-wide
police operation aimed at stopping this illegal
immigration. Hundreds of people have been arrested in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Utkan said that some foreigners were also found among the
illegal immigrants trying to enter Europe, mostly from Sri Lanka,
Egypt, Iraq as well as Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
As a country linking Europe and Asia, Turkey has always served
as a springboard for illegal immigration from some poor Asian
countries to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
