<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study of Society's Rising Madness Urged in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A high court judge today said
social scientists should find out the cause for society's growing
lack of respect for the rule of law resulting in the high crime
rate.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening the first session of the 1998 Bulawayo (the
country's second largest city) high court session, Justice
Misheck Cheda said he was particularly concerned at the high
murder and divorce rates in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"People are hitting each other with all sorts of dangerous
weapons at the slightest provocation, clearly indicating an
intention to kill and loss of respect for human life," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said social scientists should find out what had gone wrong
with the society.
</P>
<P>
Cheda said Zimbabwe's prisons were full, adding even if the
country built more courts and prisons, these would soon fill up.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said while the high court used to grant
between two and three divorces every week, this had now shot up
to 12 cases.
</P>
<P>
"The institution of marriage is gradually losing its impact
and respect. The courts have no answers to all these murder and
social problems and it is for the community and the nation to put
heads together and resolve them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The high court judge also commended the formation of the
neighborhood watch committees which had helped in reducing crime,
but however warned against the excessive use of force and what is
commonly known as "mob justice".
</P>
<P>
He urged the police to provide some form of training and
guidance for people, or leaders in the neighborhood committees,
especially those in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
He also challenged legal practitioners to have a high standard
of integrity and honesty, noting that many law firms which have
mushroomed in recent years, have faced trouble and disaster due
to lack of appropriate experience. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
