<HEADLINE> 2 Million Canadians Still Without Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 2 million people in
central Canada are still without power as the ice storm crisis
enters its second week.
</P>
<P>
And at least half of those people will remain in the dark and
cold for a week or more, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard made a public plea
for citizens to take storm victims into their homes.
</P>
<P>
At least 15 people have died as a result of a storm that
brought nearly 10 centimeters of freezing by Saturday. The ice
crushed trees and hydroelectric towers.
</P>
<P>
Many schools and public institutions remain closed here in
Ottawa and Montreal, and private companies are being urged to keep
workers off the roads.
</P>
<P>
Civil-security officials were pleading with residents without
power to head for shelters, where they can have access to warm
food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
Electrical workers are stepping up their efforts to restore
electricity to the hard-hit customers.
</P>
<P>
More than 11,400 Canadian soldiers were reported to be working
on the clean, largely around Montreal and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest ever peacetime deployment for Canadian
Forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
