<HEADLINE> 35,000 Zimbabwean Villagers Starving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 35,000 people in Omay
communal lands in Kariba, north Zimbabwe are starving and
urgently need special food relief aid from the government because
of floods, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kariba member of parliament Shumbayaonda Chandengenda today
said he had approached the Ministry of Public Service, Labor and
Social Welfare on the need for a special relief program for the
people.
</P>
<P>
He said he had registered the application following a
resolution at a Nyaminyami rural district council meeting on the
plight of the families whose crops had either been destroyed by
wildlife or washed away by floods.
</P>
<P>
"The food that was reserved from last year has been exhausted
and people are now being forced to move to Gokwe or Hurungwe in
search of food so we are appealing to the government to move on
this one with speed and also non-governmental organizations are
welcome to help," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year people in the area lost the majority of their
domestic animals to lions with other villagers losing their
homesteads to fire.
</P>
<P>
Omay falls under natural region 5 which is unsuitable for
farming but tourism as the area is common with wild animals such
as elephants, lions and buffalo.
</P>
<P>
Chandengenda said he, together with other government and
ruling ZANU (PF) officials, will embark on a week long tour of
Omay and surrounding areas to assess and discuss the food problem
facing people in the constituency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
