<HEADLINE> Holiday Road Death Toll Reduced in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The death toll on South
African roads during the holiday season since December 1 to date
was 883, 29 percent lower than in the same period last year, the
"Arrive Alive" traffic safety campaign said today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,242 people died between December 3 and January 12
last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 883 deaths in 625 accidents this year, 390 were
passengers, 282 pedestrians and 211 drivers.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal, where seaside resort Durban is located, had
more road deaths than any other provinces with 158, followed by
Gauteng and Eastern Cape with 144 each.
</P>
<P>
The least number of deaths were reported in Northern Cape with
41.
</P>
<P>
Speeding by motorists was still the number one killer on South
African roads, but passengers and pedestrians also shared their
responsibility by not wearing seatbelts and jaywalking, according
to the road safety campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
