<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants 140 Mln ECUs to Ensure Reliable Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
decided to grant 140 million ECUs (155 million U.S. dollars) to
134 energy technology projects.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced today with an aim of ensuring
reliable and sustainable energy supplies at affordable cost and
protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
The technology projects are in the fields of rational use of
energy, fossil fuels and renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
The EU grant will also finance 75 accompanying measures that
include demonstration of commercial-scale energy technology
projects, promotion and dissemination of information and project
results.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration projects are expected to provide immediate
and short-term support for important policy concerns such as
reduction of environmental hazards like carbon dioxide emissions.
</P>
<P>
The projects on rational use of energy are aimed at further
reducing investment costs while those on fossil fuels, which
represent 21 percent of the gross energy consumption of the
15-nation European Union, are aimed at overcoming the inherent
environmental problems and reducing the cost associated with its
production and use.
</P>
<P>
The renewable energy sources are mainly focused on biomass and
wind.
</P>
<P>
The EU grant will come from its funding program of Thermie that
draws 566 million ECUs (627 million dollars) from a larger funding
pool known as Joule-Thermie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
