<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Denies Reports of Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) today denied media reports that
it was discussing a merger with the largest black opposition, the
Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP).
</P>
<P>
"The recent flurry of reports about the possible merger
between the ANC and the IFP are completely unfounded and without
any substantiation" the ANC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Independent newspaper said that the ANC has swung
into action to strike a deal with the IFP to form a coalition
government in Kwazulu-Natal soon and to merge the two parties in
the longer term.
</P>
<P>
It quoted ANC insiders as saying that a merger or coalition
proposal had been circulated at a special provincial working
committee meeting of the ANC in Kwazulu-Natal, the sole province
governed by the IFP.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the proposal suggested that either the IFP be
dissolved or share a single election list with the ANC. The
report also said that ANC leaders, including former President
Nelson Mandela, new President Thabo Mbeki and Deputy President
Jacob Zuma, were propelling the merger.
</P>
<P>
The ANC denied that there were discussion on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no discussion between the ANC and IFP
leadership on the question of a merger between the two
organizations," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"For its part, the leadership of the ANC has never discussed
the matter. Interactions between the national leadership of the
ANC and the IFP have been limited to the creation of a climate
for peace and stability in the province of Kwazulu-Natal."
</P>
<P>
Mandela called for a merger between the two long-time rivals
on the eve of the ANC's 50th national conference held in
mid-December. He said in capacity as ANC president that his party
would welcome a merger with the IFP as a "progressive
development" because South Africa needed to speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
The two parties were locked in a bitter struggle for influence
in the 1980s and early 1990s, which resulted in more than 20,000
deaths.
</P>
<P>
The idea of ANC-IFP merger caused jitters among white-based
opposition parties such as the National Party and the Democratic
Party, which feared that a merger could give the already powerful
ANC too much power.
</P>
<P>
The topic has ever since then become sensitive to both the ANC
and the IFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
