<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Suspend Arms Inspection Team's Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has decided to stop any
arms inspections by the new U.N. team headed by an American, Scott
Ritter, which arrived here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement made by an official spokesman to the Iraq
News Agency, Iraq said it will block the U.N. team's inspection
starting Tuesday until it is recomposed through a balanced
participation by permanent members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi move is again setting the country in a collision
course with the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of overseeing the elimination of Baghdad's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has accused Ritter, an American officer, as a spy, and
criticized the team, with nine Americans, five Britons, a Russian
and an Australian, as not balanced in composition.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Iraq has raised the problem of lack of
balance in the make-up of UNSCOM, and stressed American and
British domination in the body is behind prolonging sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Americans with UNSCOM of "falsifying facts,
inventing lies, deliberately prolonging the inspection process and
sending false reports to the Security Council" about what Iraq has
met in terms of Resolution 687 requirements.
</P>
<P>
He said the continuation of this situation is unacceptable, and
Iraq was hoping that a reasonable balance would be effected in
UNSCOM composition and its procedure in Iraq after last crisis
over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad ordered the expulsion of the American inspectors on
November 13 in its last standoff with UNSCOM. The Americans were
allowed to return, together with their colleagues who then pulled
out to protest the eviction, only after Russian mediation a week
later.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said, those who dominate UNSCOM
headquarters in New York insist on their former position and their
biased policy.
</P>
<P>
He said that sending the team in this way underlines their
insistence and lack of respect for the demands of other states,
especially permanent members of the Security Council, to increase
their participation in UNSCOM's activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
