<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prince Philip Calls for Change in Use of Oceans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Prince Philip today
called for a sea change in the way the human use the marine
environment.
</P>
<P>
"There is overwhelming evidence that, not just the fish stocks,
but the vast bulks of the renewable resources of the oceans are
over-exploited," he said at a news conference marking the
beginning of the International Year of the Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The event, organized by the World Wide Fund For Nature (WWF),
of which Prince Philip is president-emeritus, highlighted some
growing threats facing the world's marine environment.
</P>
<P>
According to United Nations figures cited by the WWF, at least
60 percent of the world's 200 most commercially valuable fish
species are either overfished or fished to the limit.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing and destructive fishing practices have pushed
numbers of many valuable species to all-time lows.
</P>
<P>
The massive pollution of the oceans by toxic effluents and the
dumping of waste, largely caused by the increase in industrial
activities, is one of the factors that contribute to the decline
of fish stocks, the prince said.
</P>
<P>
The WWF has proposed, the prince said, that governments and the
fishing industry should ratify and adhere to international
fisheries agreements.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the WWF called for more responsible fisheries
management and the creation of an effective global network of
marine parks and reserves to safeguard critical ocean habitats.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has designated 1998 as the International
Year of the Ocean in recognition of the importance of the ocean
and the marine environment.
</P>
<P>
This, the prince said, "presents a wonderful opportunity to
initiate a campaign to ensure that there will be a reasonable
stock of fish for future fishermen and a reasonable supply of fish
for future consumers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Urges Global Support for Children's Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) chief Carol Bellamy called here today for global support
for the Children's Vaccine Initiative (CVI), saying that millions
of young children can be saved from needless death each year if
new vaccines are widely used in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a new report released by the CVI, the development
of new vaccines for diseases such as rotavirus diarrhea and
pneumococcal pneumonia in infants and the widespread deployment of
under-used vaccines for diseases like measles can save up to 12
million lives a year, mostly from infections in childhood.
</P>
<P>
"But these children's lives won't be saved without prompt
action to increase the worldwide rate of child immunization," said
Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
She noted that over 80 percent of young children are immunized
against the six major killer diseases today, compared to less than
5 percent in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"This means about 3 million fewer children die each year than
before, and it is a major public health achievement," she said.
"However, since 1990 the percentage of children vaccinated has not
increased significantly, and no new vaccines have been introduced
on a large scale in developing countries."
</P>
<P>
The CVI is co-sponsored by the UNICEF, the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the World Health Organization (WHO),
the World Bank and the Rockefeller Foundation.
</P>
<P>
"Vaccination is our most powerful weapon in the war against
infectious diseases," said J.W. Lee, executive secretary of the
CVI. "We must use it to fully protect all of the world's
children."
</P>
<P>
The CVI's strategic plan sets the following goals:
</P>
<P>
-- Control global incidence of measles, hepatitis B, Hib (which
causes meningitis and pneumonia) and rubella through broader
implementation in all regions no later than 2005;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop and introduce new, better vaccines that will reduce
deaths due to infectious diseases, and which are capable of
preventing more diseases;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop vaccines and vaccination techniques that simplify
immunization programs through such means as oral, nasal or other
forms of delivery, or reducing the number of injections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
