<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Survives No-Confidence Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu survived this evening two no-confidence motions
in the Knesset (parliament) introduced by the opposition Labor and
Meretz parties.
</P>
<P>
The two motions were voted against by 54 Knesset members of
the ruling coalition and for by 54 others from the opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
According to Israeli law, a no-confidence motion to topple the
prime minister needs support of 61 Knesset members in the
120-seat Knesset.
</P>
<P>
All five Knesset members of the Gesher Party led by former
Foreign Minister David levy, who resigned on January 4, voted for
the motions. This meant the Gesher faction has totally broken away
from the ruling Likud Group.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, Knesset Speaker Dan Tichon held a meeting
with Levy and asked him and his Gesher members not to vote for
the motions, otherwise, the government will not implement the fund
allocation agreement reached before with the Gesher Party.
</P>
<P>
Earlier during the debate, the opposition Knesset members took
turns to criticize Netanyahu, saying that his economic policy only
cares for the rich, not the poor people.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalon defended Netanyahu on
behalf of the coalition partners, saying the new state budget
approved by the Knesset last week is a balanced one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: Nepali King Still Holding Consultations Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- King Birendra was still
undecided Monday whether to dissolve parliament and hold mid-term
polls or convene a special parliamentary session to discuss an
opposition no-confidence motion against the government, the King's
Principal Press Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Royal Palace source said the King had decided to
accept the petition by Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa to
dissolve parliament and hold mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
But the same source later said that the King, who, according to
a notice from the Press Secretariat in the evening, on Monday
continued the course of consultations with parliamentary leaders,
party leaders and legal experts over the political situation in
the country, may also consult with the Supreme Court on Tuesday
before he could make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
The political situation has become uncertain after Thapa last
Thursday requested the dissolution of parliament and hold mid-term
polls, while the main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism Leninism, CPN-UML) asked the King to convene a special
session of parliament to discuss their no-confidence motion
against the government.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have claimed that their petitions are
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
In August 1995, the Supreme Court overturned a recommendation
by then Prime Minister Man Mohan Adhikari of the CPN-UML to
dissolve parliament and hold mid-term polls, and reinstated the
dissolved parliament.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that dissolution was not allowed if an
alternative government could be formed from the existing
parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
