<HEADLINE> Israeli Court Orders Extended Remand of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tel Aviv Magistrates
Court Monday ordered the extended remand until the end of trial of
a German agent sent by Hezbollah (Party of God) to launch suicide
attack.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Josef Smirak, aged 26 and a convert to Islam, was
arrested on November 28 upon his arrival at the Ben-Gurion
Airport. He was put on trial on December 25 with charges of
spying, attempting to carry out terror attack and being a member
of a terror organization.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts said each of the three charges carries a maximal
sentence of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Smirak was allegedly recruited by the pro-Iranian Hezbollah,
which has been waging a guerrilla war against Israeli occupation
of South Lebanon, during a visit to Lebanon between August and
November last year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, Smirak was sent to a training camp in the
Bekka Valley in Lebanon, where he was taught to use light weapons
and operate explosive devices.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police said Smirak was provided with video cameras and
electronic communication devices, and sent to Israel to collect
information and film densely populated areas in order to target a
site for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah handlers in Lebanon also demanded Smirak change his
passport in order to erase any traces of his Lebanese visit
before travelling to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Once he finished the fact-finding mission, Smirak planned to
fly to Turkey and contact his handlers to finalize the plan for
carrying out the suicide attack, police added.
</P>
<P>
No details about how he was found out and picked up by the
police were revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
