<HEADLINE> Egypt Sets Aside Areas for Oil, Gas Prospection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The General Petroleum Authority
of Egypt Monday invited international tenders to take part in oil
prospection in areas of 170,188 square kilometers, the Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Egyptian, Arab and foreign investors will be given the chance
to receive a concession in one or more areas individually or
jointly," Egyptian Minister of Petroleum Hamdi Ali Abdel Wahab
Al-Banbi said at a press conference held here.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for international bids will end on April 20 this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed the new prospection will be carried out
in nine areas, including those in the coastal waters of the
Mediterranean, the Western Desert, the Gulf of Suez and the South
of the Nile Valley.
</P>
<P>
He said the General Petroleum Authority received 29 bids for
prospecting oil and natural gas from international companies,
which had reflected their confidence in the climate of investment
and political and economic stability in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The oil and gas industry, one of the four largest foreign
currency earners in Egypt, produces 50 percent of the country's
total exports.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil and gas output reached 44.1 million tonnes and 9.9
million tonnes respectively in the 1995-96 fiscal year, according
to a report by the General Petroleum Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
