<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Europe Economic Growth Forecast to Accelerate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The general domestic product
(GDP) in eastern European countries will this year accelerate at
their fastest rate since these countries began their economic
transition, according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The report World Outlook 1998, a forecast of global political
and economic trends by the Economic Intelligence Unit (EIU), said
that the eastern European economies will grow by 4.1 percent in
1998 compared with 2.3 percent last year and only 0.1 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said that among the top 20 growth rates forecast for
1998, six are provided by former Eastern bloc countries, with
Bosnia at the top of the league and its output forecast to expand
by 35 percent, followed by Albania (12 percent) and Georgia (10
percent).
</P>
<P>
Although Asia provides three of the 20 slowest growing
countries in the world, with Thailand, Japan and South Korea all
suffering from the region's financial crisis, the EIU expects
China, Burma, and Vietnam to enjoy annual growth of 6 percent or
higher.
</P>
<P>
The report expected the economy of the former Soviet republic
of Turkmenistan to shrink by 2 percent to become the worst
performing economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
It also predicted that world growth will slow down to 2.7
percent during 1998 from 3.1 percent in 1996 and 1997 and this
will bring lower inflation, 4.3 percent this year, 0.8 percent
down over 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
