<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Condemns Plan on Human Cloning in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today condemned a plan announced by a U.S. doctor to conduct
human cloning.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the condemnation at the opening ceremony here of a
special session of the European Council dedicated to extending the
European Convention on Human Rights to banning human cloning.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen out of 40 European Council countries are attending
the session which will end Tuesday, and a protocol on banning
human cloning is expected to be signed by France and some other
European countries.
</P>
<P>
Besides France, Chirac called for the adoption by all world
countries of the European initiative to legally ban human cloning
on an international basis.
</P>
<P>
"We will solve nothing by banning certain practices in one
country if the researchers and doctors can do it somewhere else,"
said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we should stop the worrying deviations such as
that which has been published planned in the United States," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A doctor named Richard Seed announced that he would open a
clinic in Chicago to clone human beings to help the sterile people
have children.
</P>
<P>
Chirac was the first foreign head of state to openly condemn
the announcement by Seed.
</P>
<P>
United States President Bill Clinton has also denounced the
plan, and has asked the U.S. Congress to pass a bill on banning
human cloning as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The European protocol on banning human cloning is open for
signing by the 40 member countries of the European Union as well
as the United States, Australia, Canada, Japan, and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
But Germany, which has already drawn a lesson from its Nazi
past, said it will not sign the protocol, because its domestic law
on banning human experiments is strong enough and covers the
content of the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Britain, where the first mammal sheep clone was made last year,
will not sign the protocol either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
