<HEADLINE> UNFICYP Calls for Clearing Minefields in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Peace-Keeping Force
in Cyprus (UNFICYP) today appealed to Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides of the divided island to cooperate with it to clear
minefields and booby traps in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. made the appeal following an accident in which a
U.N. vehicle hit a mine in the buffer zone around mid-day. No one
was injured but the vehicle was damaged.
</P>
<P>
UNFICYP spokesman Waldemar Rokoszewski told reporters the
accident occurred when two Argentine non-commissioned officers
working on the Lefka road, in the buffer zone north-west of the
capital Nicosia, drove over a mine within one meter off the road
in an unmarked area.
</P>
<P>
Rokoszewski stressed this incident once more proved there is an
urgent need to clear minefields and booby traps in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He emphasised that military cooperation of both Cypriot sides,
as requested by UNFICYP, is necessary to conduct this kind of
operation.
</P>
<P>
Rokoszewski said it is not the first time a U.N. vehicle hit a
mine. According to U.N. reports, there are 39 minefields and
booby-trapped areas inside the 180-kilometer-long buffer zone,
which is patrolled by UNFICYP.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 16,000 landmines have been laid in
these areas since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and took over
the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
