<HEADLINE> N.Irish Peace Talks Resume With New Impetus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The all-party peace talks on the
future of Northern Ireland resumed today at Stormont near Belfast
after a three-week Christmas recess.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from all the main pro-British Unionist and Republican
parties attended the first session of talks, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
To add new impetus to the fragile peace talks, the British and
Irish governments agreed today on joint proposals for a political
settlement to the decades-old Northern Ireland conflict.
</P>
<P>
The plan envisages a power-sharing assembly which would
coordinate cross-border cooperation with the Irish government. It
was aimed at easing tension between majority Protestants and
minority Catholics over the future of British sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, on a visit to Tokyo, made a
flurry of phone calls to key participants over the weekend in a
bid to nail down the text of a plan to kick-start the slow-moving
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Tension was high after Christmas with four murders by rival
militias who oppose the peace process, casting a shadow on the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam managed to
persuade loyalist guerrilla inmates in the Maze prison last Friday
to renew their backing for the peace process, thus making today's
resumption of talks possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
