<HEADLINE> World Oil Price Faces Another Uncertain Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The prospect of world oil price
will be still uncertain during this week following the recent oil
price decline, the Financial Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that one of the causes leading to the
uncertainty is that 1998 may turn out to be a year in which world
oil production outstrips demand.
</P>
<P>
Another bearish factor is that the economic and currency
turmoil in some Asian countries may not only make Asian energy
demand plummet but could also hit GDP and energy demand growth in
North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prospect of greater OPEC output, together with
the expected resumption this week of Iraqi exports, also added to
the gloom.
</P>
<P>
The mild temperatures so far this year in many parts of North
America and Europe are not offering any support for oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is the forecast higher level of non-OPEC output
this year. It was reported that last year there were numerous
delays to new fields in non-OPEC countries, but this will not be
repeated this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
