<HEADLINE> US: Iraq Has No Right to "Pick and Choose" Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has no right to
determine who should carry out weapons inspections, a Clinton
administration official said today.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq cannot pick and choose who inspects its WMD (weapons of
mass destruction) programs," said the official of the National
Security Council. "This is a U.N. decision."
</P>
<P>
His statement was responding to Iraq's announcement, which said
through the Iraqi official news agency INA, "Iraq has decided to
halt the work of the inspection team headed by American Scott
Ritter ad has withdrawn permission for him to undertake any
activities inside its territory starting from Tuesday until the
composition of the team has balanced participation from the
permanent members of the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has previously accused Ritter of spying for the United
States. But Ritter, who leads one of several weapons inspection
teams, dismissed Iraq's accusation as "absolutely untrue."
</P>
<P>
The official of the National Security Council said that if the
reports about Iraq's decision were true, it would be "a clear
violation of the Security Council's demand that Iraq give (the
U.N. inspectors) full and unfettered access to all sites."
</P>
<P>
"We would expect the Security Council to very quickly review
this very latest Iraqi outrage and make clear that Iraq must
reverse its position," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein ordered American
inspectors to leave the country on the grounds of spying for the
United States, which led to complete withdrawal of weapons
inspectors and to a weapons inspection crisis bringing the two
countries on the verge of military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was resolved after Saddam, convinced by Russia's
mediation, agreed to allow the inspectors to go back and resume
their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
