<HEADLINE> Iranian Judicial Officials Called to Respect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 12 (Xinhua) - Head of the Iranian Judiciary
Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi Monday issued a decree calling on the
country's judicial officials to respect the constitution in
judicial affairs.
</P>
<P>
According the state television, Yazdi said all the judicial
officials should "exactly and accurately" carry out Article 37
and 39 of the constitution.
</P>
<P>
According to the articles, he said, no one is guilty of a
charge unless his or her guilt has been established by a competent
court.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi stressed that in order to protect the dignity and repute
of the accused, judicial officials should not reveal name or any
identity of the accused before a court ruled a verdict on him or
her.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Yazdi was forced to issue the decree under
heavy pressure from supporters of Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami who intended to bring the country under the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Many senior Iranian officials and newspapers have warned the
country's judiciary bodies to avoid "any illegal measures"
against any person, particularly illegal arrest of members of
rival political factions.
</P>
<P>
Last month, both President Khatami and Interior Minister
Abdollah Nouri stressed that the exercise of authority should be
within the framework of the country's laws and no one has the
right to impose his opinion on others.
</P>
<P>
No freedom is possible unless it is within the norms of law
and any practice of freedom outside the limits and framework of
law either breeds a state of anarchy or foments dictatorship in a
society, Khatami said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
