<HEADLINE> Ex-ECOMOG Chief Optimistic About S. Leone Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The redoubled efforts of the
west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) will ensure an end of
the peace process in Sierra Leone "in record time", the former
ECOMOG chief has said.
</P>
<P>
"There are 5,000 ECOMOG troops already in Sierra Leone and
once they are joined by the 10,000 soldiers from Monrovia,
disarmament of all factions in Sierra Leone and other assignments
will be completed without delay," said Maj.-gen. Victor Malu.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the April 22 deadline would be met for the
restoration of ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in Sierra
Leone, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The infantry general, who was until last week the ECOMOG force
commander, returned here at the weekend from the Liberian
capital.
</P>
<P>
The force, sent to Liberia eight years ago, has helped restore
peace and provide security to the country's post-war election
under a peace plan of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
It now has the mandate to restore to power by April 22 the
government of Kabbah who was toppled on May 25 last year in a
coup led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Koroma said that the ruling military junta would
be unlikely to hand over as scheduled due to the delay in
disarmament and delivery of international relief goods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, heavy fightings have been reported between the
junta forces and the pro-Kabbah Kamajor militias in the southeast
of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Despite all these, Malu said the April 22 deadline was
attainable.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that ECOMOG will have to re-double its efforts.
But I can assure you that once the order is given by the ECOWAS
leaders, the troops will move in and the job will be accomplished
in record time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malu's words coincided with those of the United Nations
special envoy to Sierra Leone, Francis Okello.
</P>
<P>
Okello reassured at the weekend that the terminal date could
be struck to in spite of the fact that disarmament has not
commenced.
</P>
<P>
According to Okello, a UN observer mission team to supervise
the peace process along with the west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG was getting prepared to move in the troubled west
African country.
</P>
<P>
The team would monitor development in Sierra Leone and to work
closely with ECOWAS and ECOMOG, and to be in contact with the
regime in Freetown, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
