<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Professors File Legal Complaint Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- With barely a year to go before
the planned January 1999 introduction of the single European
currency, the Euro, four German professors today launched a legal
complaint at the German constitutional court calling for a delay
in the Euro launch.
</P>
<P>
The complaint filed by four German professors of economics and
law, including a former member of Germany's central bank council,
Wilhelm Noelling, deals mainly with Europe's adherence to the
Maastricht Treaty criteria on Euro membership and the conditions
laid down by the German constitutional court in 1993 on the
treaty's legality.
</P>
<P>
In its 1993 decision, the German constitutional court held that
the Maastricht criteria, meant to ensure the Euro's stability,
must be strictly adhered to and that fulfillment of the criteria
must have priority over the Euro's 1999 start date.
</P>
<P>
However, the professors noted that there is obviously
widespread failure among the possible Euro candidate countries,
Germany included, to fulfill the Maastricht criteria to bring the
budget deficit to no more than 3 percent, and the national debt to
no more than 60 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the stability of the Euro is not guaranteed and it
is still premature to introduce the single currency in 1999, the
professors said.
</P>
<P>
They also argued that a premature launch of the Euro would also
violate the constitutionally guaranteed property rights.
</P>
<P>
The legal challenge to the Euro launched today came amid
general reluctance among the German population to give up their
rock-hard German mark, which has been so successful to safeguard
the country's prosperity in the post-war era, in exchange for a
common European currency whose future is still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German politicians from Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
ruling coalition as well as from the opposition parties have
largely come to the consensus that the Euro must come punctually
on January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renewed Communal Clash Displaces 50,000 in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 persons were
displaced and property worth millions of Naira destroyed during
renewed communal clash in east Nigeria's Taraba State.
</P>
<P>
The latest incident between Jukun/Chamba and Kuteps tribes was
rated as the worst since the protracted crisis began three months
ago as many house were razed, rendering thousands of people
homeless, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
One person has been confirmed to be killed in the conflict,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials have complained that the two parties involved
were culpable for burning down houses and destroying property.
</P>
<P>
A series of meetings have been held between elders of the
warring factions to find a lasting solution to the problem, but
the elite among them who resided outside the state continued to
foment trouble, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The conflict began in October last year when Takum and Ussa
local government councils were dissolved and sole administers
were appointed to run them.
</P>
<P>
The Kuteps had been protesting against the creation of Ussa
local government out of Takum, as well as the movement of their
settlements to Ussa, leaving only Jukum/Chamba in Takum local
government which the Kuteps consider as their ancestral home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
