<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Not to Inaugurate Air Base Before Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said Monday that the air
force base near the western coastal town of Paphos will not be
inaugurated before the presidential elections due to be held
on February 8.
</P>
<P>
At the daily press briefing, the government spokesman Manolis
Christofides confirmed the announcement of Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides last week that the air base will be completed and
handed over to the Cypriot government on January 24.
</P>
<P>
But he said that it will not be put into operation before the
election.
</P>
<P>
The air base is constructed under a defense pact Cyprus reached
with Greece in 1993. Under the pact, Greece will provide Cyprus
with military assistance in case the Mediterranean island is
attacked.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the air base will enable Cyprus "to
tackle Turkish provocations within the framework of the joint
defense pact."
</P>
<P>
But the announcement of opening the air base has triggered
strong reactions from the Turkish Cypriots, whose leader Rauf
Denktash has warned that the Turkish Cypriots will take immediate
steps if the Cypriot government does not back down.
</P>
<P>
"Necessary steps will be taken along with Turkey in response to
the Greek Cypriot administration's joint move with Greece,"
Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island to protect
the Turkish Cypriot minorities after a failed coup by the Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government spokesman, however, said that "Turkey
should be the last to have the right of reacting to the Republic's
efforts to bolster its defense, as our aim is to protect the
Republic from a new Turkish attack."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Greece as a guarantor of the independence of
Cyprus "has every right to take all necessary measures to fulfill
its obligations toward the Republic."
</P>
<P>
Greece, Britain and Turkey have been the guarantors of the
independence of Cyprus since it won independence from British
colonial rule in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
