<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Chief: 8 Mln Young Children Can Be Saved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Eight million young
children can escape needless death each year if a group of new
vaccines are widely used in developing nations, the Children's
Vaccine Initiative (CVI) said in a new report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The CVI is an international effort to develop and introduce new
vaccines to address diseases of public health importance. It is
the result of a unique partnership among the United Nations
Children's Found (UNICEF), the United Nations Development Program,
the World Health Organization and the Rockefeller Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The new vaccines have entered the final stage of development,
according to the CVI's report.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that another 4 million young lives could
be spared annually if widespread use of existing vaccines against
measles, hepatitis B, Hib pneumonia and meningitis, and neonatal
tetanus is strengthened.
</P>
<P>
"But these children's lives won't be saved without prompt
action to increase the worldwide rate of child immunization," said
Carol Bellamy, UNICEF's executive director.
</P>
<P>
She noted that over 80 percent of young children are immunized
against the six major killer diseases today, compared to less than
5 percent in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"This means about 3 million fewer children die each year than
before, and it is a major public health achievement," Bellamy
said. "However, since 1990 the percentage of children vaccinated
has not increased significantly, and no new vaccines have been
introduced on a large scale in developing countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
