<HEADLINE> Uganda to Cut Subsidies to Public Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
decided to reduce subsidies to the public enterprises sector by
80 percent from 208 billion Shillings (200 million US Dollars) in
1994 to 38 billion Shillings (about 35 million Dollars) by the
year 2000, a local report said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a subsidy reduction plan prepared by the Public
Enterprise Reform and Diverstiture Secretariat, it is part of a
three year budget framework paper effective in 1996-97 financial
year.
</P>
<P>
The plan noted that Uganda Railways Corporation (URC) is the
biggest recipient of government subsidies although it provides
fewer services than the road sector.
</P>
<P>
The annual cost of URC's non commercial services totalling 8.8
billion Shillings puts a great burden on government's scarce
resources and is running down both URC and government, it pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
The recently concluded financial restructuring study showed
that even with full compensation, URC shall still incur large
operating losses.
</P>
<P>
The plan was made in accordance with a preliminary subsidy
analysis of some samples of the public enterprises undertaken
with the International Finance Corporation (IFC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
