<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on Iraq not to Take Precipitous Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called on Iraq not to take "precipitous" actions
on the U.N. weapons inspection team led by an American before the
chief U.N. weapons inspector arrives in Baghdad for planned talks
next week.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the Iraqi authorities will not do anything precipitous
and wait for Richard Butler to get there," said Annan when asked
to comment at a regular press briefing on the reported Iraqi
threat to ban the U.N. weapons team.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has decided to halt the work of the U.N. inspection team
led by Scott Ritter, a U.S. marine Corps captain during the 1991
Gulf War, the official Iraqi news agency INA said earlier in the
day.
</P>
<P>
Bagdad has accused Ritter of spying for the United States and
placing obstacles in the way of implementing U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the composition of the U.N. team was not
balanced in participation of the permanent member states of the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The team is composed of nine Americans, five British, one
Russian and one Australian.
</P>
<P>
Butler is expected to arrive in Baghdad on January 19 for a
brief visit, U.N. officials said. His talks will focus on access
to suspected weapons sites and other operational issues in the
next step of the U.N. arms inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan told reporters that the U.N. team had not decided to halt
any inspections although Baghdad had decided to stop its work.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said that Butler was drafting a
letter to the Security Council officially informing it of Iraq's
decision on barring the U.N. team from carrying out its work as
from Tuesday because of its composition. 
</P>
