<HEADLINE> Jospin Promises Support to Investigation on Jewish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin promised Monday evening that the government will provide
"all means necessary" to back the investigation on the robbery
of Jewish properties in France by Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The president of the commission, Jean Matteoli, Monday
presented to Jospin the first phase report of his investigation,
in which he said that for the time being, he cannot make any
concrete proposals on how to compensate the families of the Jews
who were robbed.
</P>
<P>
He asked government to provide him with "other means" of
investigation, taking into account the "fullness and complexity
of the sources to be consulted with."
</P>
<P>
Jospin praised Matteoli for the accomplishment he has made so
far since the commission was set up one year ago by the former
government of Prime Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the commission is to determine under which
conditions the properties of Jews were robbed in France by the
Nazis and their French collaborators from 1940 to 1944.
</P>
<P>
The London international conference held in December last year
set up an international fund to compensate Jews.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be established with contribution from wartime
victorious nations such as the United States and Britain, which
seized a large number of Nazi properties.
</P>
<P>
France, which has also taken back some robbed wealth from
Germany after the war, has not decided yet whether it will join
the fund or not, and said it prefers to compensate the Jews on a
national basis.
</P>
<P>
Matteoli suggested in his report that France join the
international fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
