<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amour Stresses Zanzibar Unity, Development at </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZANZIBAR (TANZANIA), January 12 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar President
Salmin Amour today called on the people to maintain unity and
strive to develop economy today when addressing a ceremony here
to mark the 34th anniversary of the Zanzibar Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Amour said severely hit by drought and floods over the past
year as well as the on-going outbreak of cholera and malaria,
Zanzibar economy suffered greatly and hundreds of lives lost.
</P>
<P>
Despite difficulties, Zanzibar is expected to enjoy an
economic growth rate of 6.3 percent in 1997 against the 3.7
percent in the previous year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa, Prime Minister Frederick
Sumaye, and senior Zanzibar government officials inspected a
guard of honor mounted by the armed and police forces at the
Amman Stadium in a heavy rain this morning.
</P>
<P>
Amour said in his 20-minute speech that the Zanzibar
government welcomes more foreign investments and will try its
best to develop the economy in various sectors including the
private one.
</P>
<P>
He also warned leaders of certain political parties on abiding
by the Constitution instead of inciting antagonism among the
innocent people under the pretext of developing democracy and
human rights. Otherwise, they will be punished according to law,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar president also urged government officials to be
honest and businessmen to be lawful and corruption to be punished
particularly in the sector of foreign investment to guarantee the
healthy, sustainable and self-relied development of economy.
</P>
<P>
Formerly a British protectorate, Zanzibar became independent
sultanate on Dec 10, 1963. Following an armed uprising led by the
Afro-Shirazi Party on January 12, 1964, the Sultan was deposed
and a republic proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
The new government signed an Act of Union with the Tanganyika
Republic on April 26, 1964, thus creating the United Republic of
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
With its own constitution, president, government and
parliament, Zanzibar can independently handle affairs except in
the sectors of foreign relationship, national defense and
security.
</P>
<P>
A popular tourist destination consisting of two major islands,
Zanzibar and Pemba, along with several other smaller islands in
the Indian Ocean, Zanzibar is inhabited by nearly one million
residents 95 percent of which are Moslems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Tougher Penalties for Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Monday he will urge states to toughen penalties for drug
trafficking in prisons and will earmark 200 million dollars to
promote drug abstinence and treatment in the criminal justice
system.
</P>
<P>
"Somehow, jail time has to be cold turkey for those who are
addicted and must represent unemployment for those who are drug
dealers," said Barry McCaffrey, director of the Office of National
Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
Across the United States, 1.6 million men and women are in
federal, state and local prisons. In tests last year, 9 percent of
those checked tested positive for drugs behind bars, McCaffrey
said. The problem was much worse in state and local jails than in
federal prisons, he said.
</P>
<P>
Between 50 percent to 80 percent of prison population is
incarcerated because of drug- or alcohol-related crime, McCaffrey
said.
</P>
<P>
"The president believes we must have `zero tolerance' for drug
use and trafficking within our nation's prison system," a White
House statement said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced his initiative in an Oval Office ceremony.
Details were announced in advance.
</P>
<P>
Clinton directed Attorney General Janet Reno to draft
legislation, in consultation with states, that would require them
to toughen penalties for drug trafficking into and within
correctional facilities. States that did not comply could lose
prison construction funds from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also instructed Reno to take steps requiring states to
determine the level of drug use in their prisons and report
annually on whether they are making progress in reducing drug use
and availability.
</P>
<P>
States would be granted flexibility to use federal prison funds
for drug detection, offender testing and drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
A report last week by the National Center on Addiction and
Substance Abuse at Columbia University estimated that alcohol and
illegal drugs contributed to the incarceration of 80 percent of
the 1.7 million inmates in the nation's prisons. The report also
said that most of them were not being treated for addiction before
being released.
</P>
<P>
The administration has increased to 42 from 32 the number of
drug treatment centers in federal prisons and more than tripled
the number of federal inmates undergoing substance abuse treatment
-- from 5,450 in 1993 to 19,943 in the last fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
