<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Faces No Immediate Threat from East Asia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Eminent economists and
financial experts of Pakistan held a meeting here Tuesday
discussing measures to make the country responsive to the
challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The three-hour-long meeting, chaired by Minister of State and
Chief Coordinator of Pakistan 2010 Program Ahsan Iqbal, foresees
no immediate threat to Pakistan in the wake of the East Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ahsan Iqbal, while introducing the topic at the onset,
underlined the importance of the East Asian financial crisis and
its implications for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He described the challenges of globalization as a common threat
which, he said, required flexible labor market, efficient economic
system and productivity-oriented economy to cope with.
</P>
<P>
The lessons Pakistan should draw is to reduce vulnerability and
try to avoid mistakes of these countries, he believed.
</P>
<P>
Iqbal said that though Pakistan did not have structural
problems, similar to these countries, its negative effects cannot
be ignored in the backdrop of global scenario and economic
interdependence.
</P>
<P>
The minister observed that there was a need for a flexible
economic strategy in the face of the dynamic global market.
</P>
<P>
While discussing the factors of the economic upheaval in East
Asia on Pakistan, the Joint Director of the Pakistan Institute of
Development Economics (PIDE), Ashfaq Khan, forecast the likelihood
of a drop in export earnings and a pressure on trade and current
account balances.
</P>
<P>
Ashfaq believed that, to the extent that Pakistan competes with
these countries in Asian, European and North American markets, its
product will become non-competitive in these markets and may
affect export earnings.
</P>
<P>
He also foresaw difficulties for Pakistan in borrowing from the
market and its efforts to attract the much needed foreign
investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
