<HEADLINE> Indonesian President, Singapore PM Discuss Monetary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
and Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong here Tuesday evening
discussed ways to overcome the monetary turmoil that has hit
Southeast Asian countries, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Goh appreciated steps taken by the Indonesian government in
coping with the monetary crisis, especially in financial reform
based on its agreement with the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono told the press after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Singapore prime minister also expressed his
support to all the policies the Indonesian government has
formulated for its economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Goh arrived here Tuesday afternoon and he will return home
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is Goh's second visit to Jakarta since Indonesia was hit
by the crisis in July last year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister met Soeharto here last October when he
assured the Indonesia leader of his people's confidence in the
Indonesian economy and pledged to provide 5 billion US dollar
financial assistance to supplement the IMF's rescue package.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono also disclosed that Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad will also visit Indonesia in the near future to hold talks
with President Soeharto on the monetary crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is facing a deeper economic crisis as the nation's
currency, rupiah, fell to a record low of 11,000 against the US
dollar last Thursday. The rupiah has lost more than 200 percent of
its value since July last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
