<HEADLINE> China Provides 22 Million Yuan For Tibetan Blizzard Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) - China's central government has
provided 22 million yuan (about three million US dollars) in
relief funds for the Tibet Autonomous Region for the worst snow
disaster seen in decades, a Civil Affairs Ministry official said
today.
</P>
<P>
Since September, the prefectures of Nagqu, Ngari, Xigaze and
Shannan, have been hit by heavy snowstorms. By mid-December, new
snowfalls along the Himalayas cut communications between a number
of counties, towns and villages in these four prefectures, where
400,000 people and nearly 10 million head of livestock live.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Bengong, director of Disaster Relief Department
of the Civil Affairs Ministry, the department has been closely
monitoring the disaster in Tibet from the beginning. On December
3, it provided 12 million yuan in winter disaster relief funds to
the autonomous region and increased that by 10 million yuan on
January 6.
</P>
<P>
At present, all major roads have been cleared of snow and
relief materials are mainly being moved by People's Liberation
Army troops in Tibet and neighboring Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
It may take four or five years for some of the worst hit
regions, where a large number of livestock froze or starved to
death, to recover from the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
