<HEADLINE> Early 20's Steam Locomotive Joins HK Railway Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A historic Kowloon-Canton
Railway (KCR) steam locomotive, which was manufactured about three
quarters of a century ago in 1923, will be put on permanent
display at the Hong Kong Railway Museum.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's donation ceremony, Chairman of the Provisional
Regional Council Lau Wong-fat received the donation on behalf of
the council from Chairman and Chief Executive of the
Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation (KCRC) K. Y. Yeung.
</P>
<P>
At the Hong Kong Railway Museum which opened in 1985, a
collection of railway artifacts including six early KCR coaches
dated back from 1911 to 1974 and two old trolleys have been on
display.
</P>
<P>
However, no steam locomotives were available, as they were
either sold abroad or dismantled with the advent of diesel
traction in the 1950s, said Lau.
</P>
<P>
After extensive search two steam locomotives which had formerly
served on the Fanling-Sha Tau Kok branch of the KCR were found in
the Philippines. Then the KCRC negotiated with the owner of the
locomotives to arrange for the purchase and transfer back to Hong
Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
