<HEADLINE> Two Kims Urge Formation of Three-Way Consultation Organ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam and President-elect Kim Dae-jung Tuesday called for the
creation of a consultative body composed of labor, business
and political leaders to lead the country out of its economic
woes.
</P>
<P>
We would like to emphasize that the success or failure of the
three-way cooperation will determine the fate of our country, the
two Kims said in a statement issued after their second weekly
meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Government and political leaders are trying hard to persuade
labor groups to withdraw their opposition to the legalization of
layoffs and join the tripartite body.
</P>
<P>
The visiting head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
Michel Camdessus also urged business leaders on Monday to agree to
the legalization of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Permitting mass layoffs is one of the harsh key conditions of
the economic restructuring program imposed by the IMF in exchange
for a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars. Since late 1997, the
country has suffered a financial crisis caused by the collapse of
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the two Kims also hailed the agreement reached
by the nation's four largest business groups to restructure their
business and share the burden of the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, both voiced their hope that the four business groups --
Samsung, Hyundai, Lg and Sunkung -- will fulfil the agreement without
failure.
</P>
<P>
"We hope they will carry out their resolutions faithfully," the
statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
