<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soldiers Praised for Helping Tibet Blizzard Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- People's Liberation Army troops
have greatly helped relief work in the northern part of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, which has been hit by heavy snowstorms,
according to some Tibetans who have been trapped since September
by the storms.
</P>
<P>
Since January, a detachment of soldiers has covered over 2,000
km of rough road, braving sub-zero temperatures, to ferry relief
supplies to people in need.
</P>
<P>
At times, the drivers have to dig the trucks out of deep snow,
and many have had only one meal per day for the past two
weeks. Seventy percent of the soldiers have been hit by some form
of illness.
</P>
<P>
Bianba Qunpei, a Tibetan woman whose five-member family had had
not food or fuel for three days, said the People's Liberation Army
troops have saved the lives of her family.
</P>
<P>
Jia Guodong, the detachment leader, said that they have trucked
over 140 tons of relief materials to 40 villages, and have
distributed relief to at least 1,200 snow-trapped people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
