<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Called On To Coordinate Efforts In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
called on Asian nations involved in the current financial crisis
on Tuesday to coordinate their efforts in trying to tide over the
difficult time and express its willingness to help Asia overcome
the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the inaugural Asia-Europe Lecture here, Jacques
Santer, president of the European Commission, said the EU
"strongly encourage Asian countries to use this difficult moment
to coordinate their efforts in tackling the roots of the crisis."
</P>
<P>
"The EU, with over 40 years of experience in that field, is
happy to share its experiences," Santer said in his lecture,
entitled "Asia and Europe: The Road From Bangkok to London and
Beyond".
</P>
<P>
Noting that the problems in Asia are having their effect
throughout the international economy, Santer said there was little
that was inherently "Asian" about the causes of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Asian economies are very dynamic economies, with a solid
resource base, high savings ratios, skilled labor, and
entrepreneurial dynamism," he said, adding that it is "an abiding
and universal lesson" that an expanding economy requires a sound,
transparent and open policy framework, and that corrective
measures, while never popular, are most effective when taken
promptly.
</P>
<P>
"This applies in East and South East Asian as much as it
applies in Europe," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward, he said the factors which will help the
recovery are clear. The economic fundamentals of Asia remain
healthy. Sound fundamentals accompanied by sound policies, with
appropriate and stable exchange rates, transparent financial
regulation, and prudent fiscal and monetary policies, will help
ensure that confidence is quickly restored, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Europe Lecture is organized by the Asia-Europe
Foundation (ASEF) and is designed to provide leading statesmen,
scholars, scientists and other leaders of civil society with a
platform to address an informed audience on trends and issues
pertaining to Asia-Europe relations.
</P>
<P>
The ASEF, established on February 15, 1997, by members of the
Asia-Europe Meeting, seeks to promote better mutual understanding
between Asia and Europe through greater intellectual, cultural and
people-to-people exchange.  
</P>
</TEXT>
