<HEADLINE> New Oil Well Producing In South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 13 (Xinhua) -- An oil well in the eastern
part of the South China Sea drilled by the Chinese and Norwegians
went into production today.
</P>
<P>
Lufeng 22-1 was the result of cooperation between the China
National Offshore Oil Corporation and Statoil of Norway. Its
maximum daily output is estimated at 8,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
It is the ninth oilfield in the eastern part of the South China
Sea, 250 km from Hong Kong, according to CNOOC's Eastern South
China Sea Company.
</P>
<P>
Last year, total output of oilfields in the region was about 13
million tons, making it the fourth largest production base of
crude oil in China.
</P>
<P>
Lufeng 22-1 is also the deepest, at 329 meters below the
surface.  
