<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's 1997 Overall Crime Rate Reaches Decade Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's overall crime
rate for 1997 reached its lowest level in two decades,
Commissioner of Police Eddie Hui Ki-on told the media here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the work of the Commissioner of Police in the past
year, Hui said that the overall number of crimes recorded dropped
by 15 percent compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
There was a marked decrease for the fourth consecutive year in
burglaries and robberies, down by 17 percent and 24 percent
respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hui said even more pleasing is the 61 percent drop in the
number of bank, watch and gold shop robberies, adding: "Our
detection rate of 51.4 percent compares favorably with other
densely populated cities world-wide."
</P>
<P>
Throughout the year, he said, the Police Force has continued
its determined enforcement action against drug trafficking and
drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
"Operations mounted locally and internationally have been
successful in preventing the large scale importation of illicit
drugs, particularly heroin, methylamphetamine and ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
"Our long standing relationships with key overseas law
enforcement agencies have been crucial in ensuring that we play an
important role in the international fight against drugs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the 17 percent reduction in triad related crime over the
past year, Hui said the successful confiscation of criminal assets
at the end of 1997 stood at 261 million Hong Kong dollars (33.46
million U.S. dollars), with a further 244 million Hong Kong
dollars (31.28 million U.S. dollars) either frozen or pending
confiscation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said that the Commissioner of Police received a
total of 2,939 complaints against the Police Force from the public
last year, showing a decrease of 370 cases compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Corruption complaints against police officers decreased by 12.5
percent from 576 in 1996 to 512 in 1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hui said that after Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, last
year, "We continue to enforce the law in exactly the same way as
before."
</P>
<P>
The concern that police officers in senior ranks would leave
the service prior to the transfer of the power has proven to be
unfounded, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The vast majority of expatriate officers remained committed to
Hong Kong and the Police Force, with 402 remaining in the Force at
the end of 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
A recent public opinion survey shows that 43 percent of
respondents rated the Force's overall performance as good, with 30
percent considering it very good.
</P>
<P>
Encouragingly, the overall majority, 79 percent, felt a strong
sense of safety living in Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that Hong Kong remains one of the
safest and most stable societies in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
