<HEADLINE> Oman Sets Deadline for Illegal Foreign Workers to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Oman has warned illegal
expatriate workers to leave the country by March 31 or face
penalties, the Omani news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The warning issued by Oman's Ministry of Social Affairs and
Labor said that after the fixed period expires, violators will
face a one-month jail sentence and a fine of some 100
U.S. dollars, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Oman was the sixth and last Gulf Arab countries to deport
illegal foreign workers. The United Arab Emirates (UAE) led the
expulsion move in the Gulf region in 1994 and it was followed by
other Gulf countries, namely, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Kuwait and
Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The move to flush out illegal aliens is aimed at managing the
region's labor market dominated by foreigners. 
</P>
