<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Calls for Legalization of Mass Layoffs in SKorea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Managing Director Michel Camdessus said Tuesday that
South Korea has to cope wisely with great challenges that include
mass layoffs and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference before winding up his three-day visit to
South Korea, Camdessus called for South Korea to legalize mass
layoffs in order to restore the nation's financial credibility in
the world.
</P>
<P>
He said the laws on dismissals and layoffs will be essential
for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
"In the first 10 days of this year, signs in Korea were very
good in terms of normalization of the economic crisis.The latest
improvements in various macro-economic indicators also signaled the
beginning of the economic recovery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
But the nation has only won the first battle, not the whole
war, the IMF chief stressed.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said the only proper way to tackle the essential
social issue of layoffs is to strengthen tripartite dialogue among
the government, union leaders and employers.
</P>
<P>
"The nation's corporate shareholders and management should also
stand ready to share the pain of unemployed workers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
On interest rates, Camdessus said there is no way to
stabilize the economy and re-establish exchange rates at a proper level,
except through a group of policies, of which higher interest rates
are an essential component.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once the world's 11th largest economy, has been
suffering an economic crisis caused by the failure of
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions since late
1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's per capita wage last year fell to 9,400 U.S. dollars
from the previous year's 10,548 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict the economic crisis will worsen in 1998 as
the nation, under an agreement signed with the IMF for rescue
loans of 57 billion U.S. dollars, will have to completely
restructure its economy.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, with foreign exchange reserves reportedly
standing at about 9 billion U.S. dollars, South Korea has to
return roughly 25 billion U.S. dollars in foreign debts before
next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
