<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Seek Foreign Loans for Oil Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran is to borrow 4 billion
U.S. dollars from abroad in the coming Iranian fiscal year
(starting on March 21) to inject into the country's 16 oil and gas
projects, local daily Tehran Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Majlis (parliament) Monday authorized the
government to seek foreign loans for its oil and gas development
projects while it cut down the expected oil revenues with
consideration of the price slide in world market.
</P>
<P>
In its draft budget for the new year, the government of
President Mohammad Khatami forecast a foreign loan of about 6.4
billion dollars from abroad. The Majlis brought down the figure to
4 billion dollars, but allowed the government to set up companies
and offices abroad to earn most needed hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
Approving parts of the budget for the new year, the Majlis
members held pessimistic views on the country's oil revenues in
the new year due to the current falling trend of oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The government predicted a 14.9 billion dollars oil income on
the basis of 17.5 dollars per barrel, but the Majlis lowered the
expected oil price to 16 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Iran earned only 10 billion dollars from oil exports in the
first eight months of the current Iranian year and experts
believed that the annual oil income would be around 15 billion
dollars with the current oil price, some 15.5 percent less than
the projection.
</P>
<P>
Iran's oil production was 3.6 million barrels per day (bpd) in
1997 with some 2.5 million bpd for export. The country's oil
production ceiling was raised to 3.94 million bpd according to a
decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) in November.
</P>
<P>
Many parliament members have urged for a realistic projection
for the country's oil revenue in the new year budget. Debates on
details of the new budget started on Monday after the parliament
approved its outlines Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
