<HEADLINE> HK Voters Urged to Register for May Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- With only a few days left
before the deadline for voter registration on January 16, a Hong
Kong official on Tuesday urged those who have not yet registered
to act now in order to exercise their electoral rights in the
first Legislative Council elections of the Special Administrative
Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
A voter registration exercise was carried out Tuesday by the
Home Affairs Department (HAD) at the site of the new airport at
Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
Addressing hundreds of workers who are waiting to be
registered, acting Director of Home Affairs Lui Hau-tuen said: "By
taking part in the elections, you will be helping to implement the
concept of 'one country, two systems'."
</P>
<P>
He called on all Hong Kong permanent residents aged 18 and
above who ordinarily reside in Hong Kong to register without delay
so that they would be able to cast a ballot for the candidate of
their choice in the May 24 elections.
</P>
<P>
Promotion for voter registration was stepped up with the
mobilization of 30,000 Voter Registration Ambassadors (VRAs) who
began calling on some 2 million households during the Voter
Registration Week on December 6-12 last year.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by more visits conducted in the evenings by
HAD district staff as well as VRAs to households, major charitable
and commercial organizations, hospitals and various social service
centers, and the setting up of mobile registration counters at
high population concentration areas, the official added.
</P>
<P>
"The multi-facet approach has allowed us to collect more than
470,000 voter registration forms as of Tuesday. But we would like
to register as many eligible voters as possible," Lui said.
</P>
