<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano Continues to Spew hot gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Merapi volcano in
Indonesia's Central Java province has again spewed hot gas in
recent days and security around the volcano has been stepped up to
a state of alert, Antara News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The hot gas has reached 0.8 kilometer toward the Sat river, as
red-hot lava flowed to the upper reaches of the Krasak, Bebeng,
Boyong and Senowo rivers, said the report quoting an official of
local volcanological research center in Yogyakarta.
</P>
<P>
In the past week, the official said, smoke has been rising to
about 385 meters from the tip of Merapi.
</P>
<P>
The volcano's increasing activities brought about one volcanic
earthquake, 12 multi-phase earthquakes, 19 low-frequency
earthquakes, 10 tectonic earthquakes and 42 occasions of fallout
tremors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Merapi volcano is classified by vulcanologists as an
"explosive" type, similar to the volcano which devastated the
Caribbean island of Martinique at the turn of the century and left
29,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
Merapi rises to a height of 2,926 meters. To the east it
overlooks the most famous Indonesian monument, the Buddhist temple
of Borobodur, and 30 kilometers to the south the university city
of Yogyakarta, where one million people live.
</P>
<P>
The region is a geologically unstable area which makes up part
of the Pacific "ring of fire". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
