<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Fund Redemptions Modest Despite Market Volatility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Sales activities of unit
trusts were subdued in November last year, with gross sales
dropping to a meager 255.12 million U.S. dollars, the Hong Kong
Investment Funds Association (HKIFA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The general investment sentiment in Asia remained weak in the
month as uncertainties over the outcome of the Asian currency
turmoil lingered on, said Peter Lord, chairman of the HKIFA.
</P>
<P>
However, Lord said, "although the lingering uncertainties
resulted in sluggish sales and continuous net outflows in certain
sectors in November, redemptions were not massive nor took place
at a scale that exacerbated the financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
In fact, new outflows for November were low at 1.65 million
U.S. dollars. Moreover, six out of the 14 fund sectors actually
managed to register new inflows.
</P>
<P>
Among the various sectors that registered net inflows, bond
funds that is viewed as a safe haven was the most popular,
recording net inflows of 39.69 million U.S. dollars for the month.
</P>
<P>
Another haven in times of high market volatility -- cash funds
-- took the second place, registering net inflows of 11.10 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong equity funds managed to register net inflows, albeit
marginal, in November, with gross inflows amounting to around 31
million U.S. dollars
</P>
<P>
Among all Asian sectors, Hong Kong equity funds was the only
sector that had managed to register net inflows in all 11 months
in 1997, although the level of net inflows had dwindled in
November.
</P>
<P>
The HKIFA consists of 45 fund management companies as
full/overseas members. It has about 40 associate members including
 trustees and other professionals which are involved in the
creation and administration of funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
