<HEADLINE> Malaysia Ready for Talks with Thailand on PULO Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is ready to
discuss with its neighbor Thailand on the issue of a Thai rebel
group known as the Pattani United Liberation Organization (PULO)
whose members are said to be trained in Malaysia, its Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia voiced its readiness to Thai Deputy Foreign Minister
Sukhumbhand Paribatra who called on Abdullah here Tuesday to make
arrangements for the official visit by Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan to Malaysia next month, the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported, quoting Abdullah himself.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Thailand was aware of Malaysia's
"non-interference" stand in the internal affairs of its neighbors
or other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said he told Sukhumbhand that he was open on that issue and
if Thailand had information, it could discuss the matter during
Surin's visit.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want Malaysia to be used as a base by any groups from
neighboring countries...that's our policy," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
"Sukhumbhand informed me that if Thailand has information and
proof on the matter, it will be conveyed by Surin," Abdullah was
quoted as telling reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the visit, Surin's first official visit to Malaysia since
his appointment to the post, Abdullah said Surin was keen to
discuss the Malaysia-Thailand Joint Commission meeting and
unresolved joint border issues.
</P>
<P>
The Thai foreign minister is also expected to propose several
measures to enhance bilateral ties particularly in tackling
problems arising from the currency crisis faced by Malaysia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar earlier on January
4 described as unfounded reports that Malaysia was the training
ground for the PULO, saying Malaysia does not allow foreign
separatist groups to train in this country.  
</P>
