<HEADLINE> Teenager Beats Odds and Stars to Become World Champ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 13 (Xinhua) -- American Kristy Kowal surged
ahead in the home stretch to become the women's 100m breaststroke
world champion on Tuesday, beating a strong field which included
Olympic gold medalist, European champion and world No.1 ranked
swimmer.
</P>
<P>
Kowal, 19, quickened her stroke with 20 meters left and touched
home first in her personal best time of 1:08.42.
</P>
<P>
She looked at the timeboard in disbelief. After several
seconds, Kowal realized that she was the winner, pumping her fist
into air in celebration.
</P>
<P>
Australian Helen Denman got the silver medal in 1:08.51, 0.15
clear of bronze medalist Lauren van Oosten of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Reigning world champion Agnes Kovacs missed the medal podium by
a narrow 0.02 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Penny Heyns, South Africa's Olympic champion and world record
holder, finished fifth in 1:08.77 with world top-ranked swimmer
Samantha Riley of Australia in sixth place.
</P>
<P>
Riley, a pre-race title favorite, turned first at the wall but
lost momentum as the race went to the home stretch. She clocked
1:08.80, 1.14 seconds outside of her 1997 world best time.
</P>
<P>
Australia might have got some solace, if not happiness, in the
men's 4x200m relay final, in which they had boasted to produce the
first record at the championships.
</P>
<P>
The Aussie quartet, paced by newly crowned 200m freestyle king
Michael Klim, triumphed in a new meet mark of 7:12.48, 4.29
seconds faster than the Netherlands which picked the silver medal.
</P>
<P>
Britain won the first medal in the championships as it timed
7:17.33 for third place.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Claudia Poll came in first to take the women's
200m freestyle top honor.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican star, who possesses a deadly-efficient stroke
and blinding speed that can be unleashed at any time, clocked
1:58.90 for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Martina Moravcova of Slovakia lifted the silver medal in
1:59.61, 0.31 clear of bronze medalist Jilia Greville of Australia.
</P>
<P>
American Tom Dolan was the other Olympic champion who remained
unbeaten here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dolan timed 4:14.95, over two seconds away from his world
record but good enough to beat Dutchman Marcel Wouda into second
spot.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Curtis Myden was third in 4:16.45.
</P>
<P>
Dolan was the only fourth American to win back-to-back world
championship titles. The others include Tom Jager, Matt Biondi
and Janet Evans.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Russian Dmitry Sautin beat his closest rival by over
50 points to grab the men's 3m springboard title.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Zhou Yilin got the silver medal in 694.92 and Vassiliy
Lisovskiy of Russia took the bronze in 651.60.
</P>
<P>
Russian Olga Sedakov was crowned in the synchronized swimming
solo, in which she put up a nearly perfect performance.
Frenchwoman Virginie Dedieu came out second with Japanese Miya
Tachibana in third place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
