<HEADLINE> China Expresses Regret Over Taiwan Leader's Philippines Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China's Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Shen Guofang, at a press conference this afternoon,
expressed regret that the Philippines allowed the "Premier" of
Taiwan's "Executive Yuan" Siew Vincent to visit.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is demanding that the Philippine
government stick to its commitment to follow the "one China"
policy to avoid damaging bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Shen reiterated China's stance against any official relations
and exchanges with Taiwan by any country that has diplomatic
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China has noticed the financial
difficulties encountered by some Southeast Asian and other
countries and that China understands their efforts to obtain
economic assistance within the framework of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF). But, he said, the Chinese government is
firmly opposed to Taiwan authorities participating in any form in
any official arrangements or activities in this.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that these countries will adhere to the "one China"
stand and be alert to Taiwan authorities' attempts to use money
to carry out "one China, one Taiwan" or "two Chinas" activities.
</P>
<P>
Shen said that China holds that Taiwan authorities can only
provide assistance to these countries through unofficial
channels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
