<HEADLINE> Macao Financial System Firm Before Currency Crisis: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Macao monetary chief said on
Tuesday that the currency crisis in Southeast Asia has brought no
major impact on Macao's financial system, but it will be a blow
to Macao's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese News Agency Lusa quoted Manuela Morgado,
president of the Macao Monetary and Foreign Exchange Authority
(AMCM), as saying that the impact of the Southeast Asian currency
turmoil and the stock market turbulence on Macao's financial
sector was "not very significant."
</P>
<P>
She said that large part of the Macao monetary authority's
investments were held in U.S. treasury bonds, and the local
banking sector had no Hong Kong dollar debts.
</P>
<P>
Macao's financial stability depends on the maintenance of the
local currency's peg to the Hong Kong dollar and the latter's peg
to the U.S. dollar, she said.
</P>
<P>
She defended Hong Kong government's "intransigent defense" of
the HK dollar's peg to the U.S. dollar as a "correct attitude,"
even if that means to accept a slowdown of the economy.
</P>
<P>
However, she admitted that Macao's economic growth could be
affected by the crisis. The HK dollar's peg has resulted in higher
interest rates in both Hong Kong and Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
