<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Register First Rebound in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks rose 7.37
percent Tuesday for the first gain of the new year, rebounding
from a consecutive eight-day plunge since December 31 last year.
</P>
<P>
The impressive technical rebound was owed to overnight gains on
the Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng index gained 598.94 points to close at
8,720.00 following seven consecutive sessions of losses of the new
year after the Wall Street overnight reversed a sharp early
slide and ended up.
</P>
<P>
The day's session recorded a turnover of 11.038 billion HK
dollars (about 1.426 billion US dollars), against the 12.332
billion HK dollars on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index rose 212.68 points, or 2.61 percent, to
open at 8,333.74 in the morning and it gained 407.23 points, or
5.01 percent, to close at 8,528.29 at midday.
</P>
<P>
The index had dropped 773.58 points to a near three-year low in
Monday's trading amid high interest rates and the collapse of Hong
Kong-based Peregrine Investment Holdings, once Asia's largest
independent investment bank.
</P>
<P>
Factors believed to be behind the rising local market on
Tuesday included lower interbank rates, improved Asian financial
markets and the government land auctions for two sites with
lower-than-expected prices offered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
