<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Adopts Document Outlining PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet Tuesday
adopted a document that outlines the obligations it demands the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to fulfill before Israel
carries out second further troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The document was compiled by Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh,
who was appointed by the cabinet as head of a ministerial
committee which will monitor the PNA's fulfillment of these
obligations.
</P>
<P>
The obligations, outlined according to the Hebron accord
signed a year ago, requires the PNA to revise the Palestinian
Charter calling for Israel's destruction, fight terror and
prevent violence against Israel, and restrict the number of
Palestinian police forces and the PNA activities in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted the document as stressing that any Israeli
further troop redeployment is contingent on the PNA's fulfillment
of these commitments.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the establishment of the ministerial monitoring
committee, the cabinet also considered the involvement of the
United States in the follow-ups. The U.S. as the leading mediator
mediated and witnessed the signing of the Hebron accord.
</P>
<P>
No timetable was set in the document for the PNA to fulfill its
commitments, but Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
said that he favors a five-month trial period to assess the PNA
actions in these above-mentioned areas.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of the United States, Netanyahu announced
last Thursday that he would split the decision on the second
Israeli further redeployment in the West Bank into two decisions.
</P>
<P>
The first decision on the pullback scope is to be made ahead of
his visit to Washington to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton late
this month, while another decision be made five months later on
whether to carry out the pullback based on the PNA's fulfillment
of its commitments.
</P>
<P>
This move was termed as an attempt to further delay the
redeployment in order to avoid hardliners within Israel's
splintered coalition from toppling the government.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is also to meet with PNA leader Yasser Arafat in
a bid to narrow the gap between the sides so to advance
the stalled peace process. PNA officials have warned that a
failure of the Washington talks could lead to renewed popular
Palestinian struggle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, US Should Increase Cooperation: Jiang Zemin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, in a
meeting this afternoon with William Perry, former U.S. secretary
of defense, said that China and the U.S. should increase dialogues
and cooperation to ensure peace and prosperity in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining and developing stable Sino-US cooperative relations
are in the fundamental interests of the two peoples and conducive
to world peace and prosperity, he said, and spoke positively of
the efforts of Perry and members of his delegation at improving
relations between the two countries and between the two countries'
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Jiang spoke of his visit to the US last year, which, he said
enabled him to see for himself the US people's friendship towards
the Chinese people and the US people's desire to develop Sino-US
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that, for the fundamental interests of the two peoples
and for world peace and development, the two countries' leaders
decided to establish stable Sino-US cooperative relations oriented
to the 21st century, and that this was an important step forward
in Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that the Taiwan issue has always been a key
issue and the most important and sensitive one in bilateral
relations, and that the key to healthy and steady bilateral
relations is strictly abiding by the three Sino-US joint
communiques and properly handling the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Perry said that the American people think that Jiang's visit to
the US last year was successful and further improved bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides should seize the opportunity and implement the
various agreements the two leaders reached and that the US should
observe the principles spelled out in the three joint communiques,
he said, and added that he hopes the two countries and their
military forces can increase exchanges and cooperation for greater
progress in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Among those who were present at the meeting were Vice-Chairman
of China's Central Military Commission, State Councillor and
Minister of National Defense Chi Haotian, and former National
Security Advisor to the US President Brent Scowcroft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
