<HEADLINE> CIC, AFP Sign on World Cup Soccer Online Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- China Internet Corporation
(CIC) and Agence France-Presse (AFP) signed here on Tuesday an
agreement to provide landmark Chinese language online coverage of
this summer's World Cup finals soccer tournament in France.
</P>
<P>
Peter Yip, CIC's Executive Vice-Chairman, said: "We are
delighted to be participating with a world-class media
organization of the caliber of AFP, and using advanced multi-media
Internet technology, to bring the World Cup to the Chinese
language audience."
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted to be working with CIC on what is without
doubt the world's biggest sports event in a country with possibly the
largest soccer following," Denis Brulet, AFP Regional Director for
Asia-Pacific, said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement CIC and AFP will provide fast-breaking
coverage of the World Cup finals slated for June 10 to July 12.
The service will reach Chinese football fans via CIC's China Wide
Web in both Chinese and English.
</P>
<P>
World Cup followers on China's mainland will not only have
access to real-time reports on all 64 matches but will also see a
wide selection of photos and graphics on the China Wide Web
beginning February 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The China Wide Web service will include access to a huge soccer
database compiled by AFP including extensive information on the 32
teams in the finals, profiles of team managers, coaches and
players and descriptions of stadiums and the French cities hosting
the matches.
</P>
<P>
A database on the history of the World Cup will provide
information on previous tournaments going back to the inaugural
tournament in 1930.
</P>
<P>
China Internet Corporation has been responsible for the
creation of the China Wide Web, an online business information
collaboration and communication system that spans China.
</P>
<P>
China Wide Web is supported through a series of alliances with
global news and information corporations, and has developed its
network infrastructure through partnerships with the world's
leading computer hardware and software companies.
</P>
<P>
A strategic partnership with China's Ministry of Post and
Telecommunications has resulted in CIC's China Wide Web service
being available to Internet viewers in more than 200 cities in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
