<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Sell Two Tons of Elephant Tusks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- A Mozambican wildlife official
has said the country might sell two tons of elephant tusks soon
under the arrangement of the Convention on International Trade of
Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Noticias today quoted Sansao Bonito, director
of the National Bureau for Forest and Wild Animals, as announcing
the news here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a group of CITES experts will visit
Mozambique this month in a bid to be acquainted with the
situation of the country's accumulated tusks since 1989, when
tusk sale was first banned.
</P>
<P>
Individuals and institutions who own ivory tusks must make
their sale to the National Bureau for Forest and Wild Animals or
to other relevant provincial agencies, Bonito said.
</P>
<P>
"Inspection measures will be implemented, under which those
violating the rules will be punished," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Bonito revealed that those allowed for sale include raw tusk
as well as tusk products. They could be sold after appraisal by
international experts.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the efforts by the international community to
restrict tusk trade, especially in African countries.
</P>
<P>
"When some of the countries still have a large reserve of
tusks, there could be no talking about a complete ban on tusk
trade," said the director.
</P>
<P>
The investigation results by the CITES experts will be
announced at an international meeting in March, when decisions on
the ways of tusk sale are made.
</P>
<P>
Bonito indicated that there might be two ways for the sale,
one to sell them to Japan, which is a potential consumer of
tusks; the other is to make the sale to donors' group before they
are destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Airport Not Affected by Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Macao Airport has seen a normal
operation this year amid a currency crisis in Southeast Asia, a
senior airport executive said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Joao Moreira, chairman of the Board of Directors of the Macao
Airport Franchise Company (CAM), told Xinhua that the airport has
seen no obvious decline in its passenger flow.
</P>
<P>
About 4,000 passengers have traveled via the airport each day
this year and the figure is just as normal as in any other day
last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, about half of the passengers are from Taiwan, which
has not been strongly hit by the crisis. Taiwan passengers still
go to China's mainland via Macao by using the quasi-direct flight
service between Taipei, Kaohsiung and several mainland
destinations.
</P>
<P>
Moreira predicted that the passenger flow will not see a
decline until April as the holidays of the Chinese Lunar New Year,
or the Spring Festival, draw near.
</P>
<P>
The chairman remains firm on his company's set target of an
expected passenger growth rate of 12.8 percent in 1998. He said
more promotion effort will be made this year in China's mainland
to attract more mainland passengers to travel abroad via Macao.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the company plans to increase its cargo shipment
service this year.
</P>
<P>
The airport handled about 2 million passengers in 1997, up 50
percent from 1996, while its cargo shipments reached 45,540 tons,
up 82 percent. 
</P>
