<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK New Airport Opens in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will open the new
airport at Chek Lap Kok on July 6, 1998, the first Monday of the
month, a government spokesman announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On opening, the new airport, to be known as the Hong Kong
International Airport, will be of world class with supporting
facilities, including the Airport Railway, ready for operation.
</P>
<P>
"We have to ensure what is available on Day One is a world
class airport supported by efficient transport arrangement," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Judging from current works progress, the new airport should be
ready for operation in late April, and the Mass Transit Railway
Corporation has confirmed that the Airport Railway will be
available in late June as originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The new airport had originally been scheduled to open in April
this year.
</P>
<P>
"The commissioning of the new airport and the Airport Railway
in tandem will be significant. It will also denote the successful
conclusion of the 155-billion-HK-dollar (20 billion U.S. dollars)
Airport Core Program," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
On July 6, which is the first Monday in July, the new airport
will start operation "as we need a Sunday night with lighter road
traffic to facilitate a smooth airport relocation exercise and as
air traffic also happens to be lighter on Monday," the spokesman
noted.
</P>
<P>
The new airport is the largest single construction project ever
undertaken in Hong Kong. Unlike the existing Kai Tak airport, the
new one will be able to operate around the clock.
</P>
<P>
During its initial operation, it will be able to handle up to
35 million passengers and 3 million tons of cargo a year. Upon
full development in the longer term, the airport will have an
annual throughput capacity of 87 million passengers and 9 million
tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 29.5 million passengers and 1.56 million tons of cargo
passed through Kai Tak. According to Airport Council
International's figures, Hong Kong ranks first in international
air cargo throughput and third in terms of international
passengers.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Railway is designed to carry about 40 percent of
air passengers. It will take passengers from Central, Hong Kong
Island, to the new airport in 23 minutes. In-town check-in
facilities are available at the Central Station and Kowloon
Station.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
