<HEADLINE> Electronic Purse Becoming Popular in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Seven more Hong Kong banks
Tuesday joined the line of issuers to Visa Cash, a stored value
card known as "electronic purse".
</P>
<P>
Visa International singed agreement Tuesday with the seven new
member banks, including the Bank of East Asia, Chekiang First
Bank, Citibank, Hong Kong Chinese Bank, Shanghai Commercial Bank,
Wing Hang Bank and Wing Lung Bank.
</P>
<P>
So far, 21 banks in Hong Kong have joined the electronic cash
payment system, with 13 sister banks under the Bank of China Group
and Standard Chartered Bank as the pioneers.
</P>
<P>
Visa Cash was first introduced in Hong Kong in August 1996. As
a handy and convenient "electronic purse", Visa Cash card reduces
the need to carry cash or coins for small payment, say, at fast
food chains, vending machines and petrol stations.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, a total of 210,000 Visa Cash cards have been issued
in Hong Kong. The transaction volume has exceeded 28 million HK
dollars (3.6 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raymond Chan, executive vice president and general manager of
the Greater China Region of Visa International, said that by the
end of 1998, the number of Visa Cash cards is expected to top
400,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
