<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets Omani Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Tuesday met with Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs
Yussef ben Alawi who is believed to be mediating an end to the
mounting tensions between Egypt and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The Omani official, after talks with Mubarak this morning at
the presidential palace, said he delivered a message from Sultan
Qaboos Bin Said to Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed means of boosting the distinguished
Omani-Egyptian ties in all fields. President Mubarak's views were
identical to the Omani ones," said Alawi, without disclosing the
content of the message he delivered.
</P>
<P>
Alawi met with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa upon his
arrival here late Monday from the Qatari capital of Doha on an
previously unannounced two-day visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Moussa has said Alawi's talks here would deal with a number of
issues including the Gulf affairs, the Arab situation in general
and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
But diplomatic sources speculated that his current mission is
designed to bridge the growing gap between Cairo and Doha despite
previous mediation efforts by Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
"Calming down the Arab atmosphere was a duty and we have
tackled this subject during the meeting (Tuesday). The issue was
also raised when I was in Doha," Alawi told reporters, without
elaborating.
</P>
<P>
In an indication of no immediate mediation breakthrough, he
said the date of a meeting of the Damascus Declaration Group has
not been set. The meeting slated in Doha was put off after Moussa
said he could not attend on December 1 to 2, 1997, because of the
"tension" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Damascus Declaration Group, which was formed in the
immediate aftermath of the 1991 Gulf War to develop security and
political links, groups eight countries, namely, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman, Syria and
Egypt. They were allied against Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Qatari relations deteriorated in October when Egypt
boycotted the fourth Economic Conference of the Middle East and
North Africa in Doha.
</P>
<P>
Qatar introduced a ban on the entry of nationals of Egypt
alongside other nine countries as a security precaution for the
Doha conference, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to their row were Qatar's charges that Egypt had
plotted the 1996 coup attempt to overthrow the Gulf sheikdom's
emir. Egypt rejected the charges and demanded for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
The crisis failed to patch up the difference despite intensive
mediation by Saudi Arabia, which facilitated a meeting in the
Saudi capital Riyadh between the Egyptian and Qatari leaders at
the end of November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Worsens in Kenya, Killing Three </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Three youths were drowned,
hundreds of people displaced, and transport and communication were
cut off as heavy rains pounded different parts of Kenya at the
weekend, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two 15-year-old boys were swept away by swollen River Sosian
near Turbo, Uasin Gishu while the police are still looking for
the body of a 14-year-old boy who was drowned in River Rusumu in
Kakamega, western Kenya.
</P>
<P>
As more bridges and roads continued to be cut off by
landslides, the rains brought by the El Nino weather phenomenon
fell relentlessly, causing flash floods.
</P>
<P>
The situation marred the nationwide schools' opening day
Monday and frustrated travellers in various parts of the eastern
African country as most roads were impassable.
</P>
<P>
Rains which came down in torrents in capital Nairobi Sunday
night made a mess of the transport system, ruining the prospects
of a smooth return-to-school day with hundreds of commuters were
left stranded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, traffic along the busy Mombasa-Nairobi road was cut
off for several hours following heavy floods which have washed
away Kambu bridge on the road. Mombasa is the country's
second-largest city and coastal capital.
</P>
<P>
Lorries and trucks transporting food, beverages and fuel to
the world-famous Maasai Mara National Park in western Kenya have
been stuck along the muddy Narok-Maasai Mara road for several
days.
</P>
<P>
Hotels, lodges and tented camps which rely on air transport
have been able to receive guests but game drives are impossible.
</P>
<P>
Along the Athi River which burst its banks over the weekend,
hundreds of families were displaced. Frightened residents fled
from their homes with only a few belongings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
