<HEADLINE> Barclays Bank in Zambia to Lay off 300 Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Barclays Bank in Zambia will
lay off 300 workers this year as part of the on-going
restructuring program to reduce its staff to 800.
</P>
<P>
The 300 staff will, however, go on voluntary redundancy scheme
set up by the bank three years ago, the local newspaper Financial
Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Iain Knapman, the bank's Managing
Director, as saying that the bank also plans to reduce the number
of expatriates by 40 to 50 percent over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
These are aimed at improving levels of production and meet
customers demands for more efficient service and great product
availability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring entails clustering branches into one business
unit, a move seen as a catalyst to exploit the bank's growing
information system functionality.
</P>
<P>
"The growing demand for more products, more complex products
and greater operational efficiency calls for specialised skills,
hence the need to use the limited experts through wider
responsibilities across a number of branches within a cluster
than in a single branch" Knapman noted.
</P>
<P>
The bank will retain its in-house training capability and
focus on in-branch training and specialized product-based
courses, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
