<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Rebound Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) rebounded sharply Tuesday, pushing
the benchmark Composite Index (CI) above the level of 500 points.
</P>
<P>
The 100-stock CI climbed steadily and touched a high at 507.01,
before settling at 503.89 points, a 26.32 point or 5.5 percent
gain over Monday's closing.
</P>
<P>
The Emas Index also rebounded 5.47 points to 128.42, the
Industrial Index recouped 35.55 points to 1,016.53 and the Second
Board Index recovered 4.82 points to 132.34.
</P>
<P>
Gainers overwhelmed losers by 621 to 103 while 84 counters were
traded unchanged and 100 untraded.
</P>
<P>
The main board's ready turnover expanded to 157.981 million
shares valued at 368.413 million ringgit (about 80 million U.S.
dollars) from 126.038 million shares worth 286.346 million ringgit
(about 62.2 million U.S. dollars) Monday.
</P>
<P>
Second Board volume rose to 14.166 million shares valued at
22.712 million ringgit (about 4.9 million U.S. dollars) from
Monday's close of 11.895 million shares worth 21.299 million
ringgit (about 4.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off market deals fell to 7.504 million shares valued at 16.172
million ringgit (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars) from 11.112
million shares worth 42.017 million ringgit (about 9.1 million
U.S. dollars) Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market's rebound was supported by local
players as the local currency -- the ringgit stabilized, which
closed at 4.6000 to the U.S. dollar Tuesday against Monday's
4.6350/50.
</P>
<P>
They said the recovery in Hong Kong and Singapore bourses also
helped to calm jittery investors here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
