<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Pledges to Take Firm Step to Overcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
agreed that Indonesia needs to take firm steps along with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) in a bid to build confidence to
the country's economy, an U.S. official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Treasury Secretary of the United States Lawrence Summers
said this when explained his meeting with President Soeharto at
his residence in the morning.
</P>
<P>
Summers, who arrived here on Monday, had a 90-minute discussion
with Soeharto. "President Soeharto and I had a very fruitful
discussion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Appearing to the press for only two minutes, Summers did not
give reporters a chance to ask a single question.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the head of state has pledged that the
Indonesian government would implement the economic reforms as
agreed upon with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"Our team brings here President Bill Clinton's message about
the importance of economic reforms (in Indonesia)," he said before
taking a car to American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, after accompanying Soeharto in receiving Summers,
Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said, "what President Clinton
conveyed (through Summers) are things that had long been in
President Soeharto's mind and (they) will be implemented."
</P>
<P>
Summers, as a special envoy of President Clinton, said here
Monday night after a three-hour meeting with Indonesian Finance
Minister Mar'ie Muhammad that he remained optimistic that
Indonesia's economy will recover.
</P>
<P>
Summers' visit was triggered by recent monetary crisis in
Indonesia. The Indonesian rupiah declined to a historic low of
11,000 per dollar last Thursday. The currency has lost more than
200 percent of its value since July last year.
</P>
<P>
The drastic fall of rupiah has also slowed down the country's
economic activities and threatened businesses with closure and
mass layoff.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the IMF agreed to provide 23
billion U.S. dollar financial and technical loans to Indonesia in
exchange for conducting economic and financial reforms in the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF was reportedly dissatisfied over Indonesia's
reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
