<HEADLINE> Share Prices Recover Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices recovered on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
rose sharply by 83.05 points to close at 1156.52 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that share prices finished higher after seven
straight days of sharp falls in what was termed a technical
rebound.
</P>
<P>
Relative stability in regional currencies and other Asian stock
markets provided investors with the opportunity to hunt for
bargains, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, they added that it remained unclear if the gains were
sustainable. Banking and property shares, which had plunged
recently, led advancers.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 354.25 million units,
valued at 612.11 million Singapore dollars (343.88 million US
dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 313 to 72, while 227
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Wing Tai was the most actively traded counter as it registered
a turnover of 31.68 million units. It was followed by Guthrie GTS
which had 26.49 million shares traded. DBS (Development Bank of
Singapore) Land was next with 23.66 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 2.1 Singapore dollars to finish at 30.6
Singapore dollars. Khong Guan increased by 1.8 dollars to end at
3.8 Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) picked up by
1.7 Singapore dollars to close at 14.2 dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, C Properties was the biggest loser as it
declined by 6.5 dollars to end at 10.5 Singapore dollars. Chem
Ind. fell by 30 cents to close at two Singapore dollars, while
BerLand was 27.5 cents lower at 23 cents.  
</P>
