<HEADLINE> Uganda to Launch Five-Year Health Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government will
present a five-year health plan within two months to upgrade the
country's health standard, The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of the plan Herman Kyabagu said the plan will
focus on major causes of disease and death in the country and to
empower communities and households to improve their health
condition.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also consider health-related issues such as
poverty alleviation and sanitation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The final draft have been made, and it will be presented to a
conference of health donors in April.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the conference include World Health
Organisation (WHO), Medical Bureaux of Catholics, Protestants and
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
WHO and three private donors' organisations had met government
officials from health, planning, finance departments on the plan.
The officials said the plan will meet the basic requirements for
health services to all people.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also deal with non-communicable diseases which
are on the increase in addition to the infectious ones. Uganda
shares the global burden of more than 30 new highly infectious
diseases including AIDS which emerged in last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Hatib Jnie, WHO's resident representative, said the plan
should strengthen the existing health facilities in addition to
bringing in new ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
