<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Williams Beats Hingis in International Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- American black girl Venus
Williams overcame dehydration and cramps to upset world No.1
Martina Hingis in an extraordinary three-set second round match at
the Adidas International Tennis Tournament in Sydney today.
</P>
<P>
Williams took an injury timeout early in the deciding set and
Hingis at 5-5 in the third during a marathon two hour 12 minute
classic played in 29 degrees celsius heat.
</P>
<P>
The world No.32 won 3-6, 6-4, 7-5 on a scorching tennis court
in Sydney to avenge her 1997 US Open final loss to Hingis, the
winner of three Grand Slams last year.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in nearly two years that the defending
champion had lost her opening match of a tournament. She went
down to Japan's Nana Miyagi in three sets at the Lipton
Championship in Florida in March, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Williams, who had failed to win a set in three previous matches
with the Swiss star, said she had never suffered such distress
during a match.
</P>
<P>
"I'd describe it as cramps and heat sickness. I had never had
it before," Williams told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't want to quit, I had come so far in the heat, I knew I
couldn't give up ... I hadn't drunk enough fluid.
</P>
<P>
However, Williams said she was not targeting Hingis' No.1
position this year but admitted it was a goal in future years.
</P>
<P>
Hingis believed she threw away the match after winning the
first set and leading 3-1 in the next but remained defiant.
</P>
<P>
"I should have won this match but she played better, played
smarter".
</P>
<P>
"She made lots of unforced errors in the first set and I took
advantage of that".
</P>
<P>
"I was waiting for her to make mistakes. She didn't make them
after the first set."
</P>
<P>
Williams was level at 1-1 in the third set when her right leg
cramped as she attempted to serve.
</P>
<P>
After treatment courtside and in the change rooms she returned
to massive cheers from the capacity 7,000 crowd.
</P>
<P>
There appeared little hope for the lanky 17-year-old as she
lost three successive points to lose her serve. She barely moved
during that game.
</P>
<P>
But Williams found another gear as she attempted to end each
point quickly with power shots from both sides of the court.
</P>
<P>
She broke Hingis' serve to love to level at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
Then Williams held serve to lead 3-2 before she broke Hingis
for 4-2 and a major upset appeared in the making.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, though, hasn't reached the top without showing
tremendous determination when in trouble, and she crawled out of a
corner to level at 4-4 after breaking back.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss 17-year-old called for an injury timeout two games
later as she suffered mild cramping and heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
The time off court helped Williams more than her opponent as
the American converted eight straight points to win the set and
the match.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
