<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Meets US Congressman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad met here Tuesday U.S. Congress Finance Committee
Chairman William Roth to discuss on cooperation between Malaysia
and the U.S. to overcome the current economic crisis in Southeast
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"There was a general exchange of views on how the U.S. could
actually help overcome the economic crisis which I cannot reveal,"
Malaysian Foreign Ministry's Undersecretary for Southeast Asia and
South Pacific Division Mohamed Arshad M. Hussain told reporters
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, during their one-hour talk, they did not come out with
specific proposals, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mahathir explained to Roth the measures Malaysia
was taking to tackle the economic woes and reiterated Malaysia's
refusal to accept International Monetary Fund (IMF) assistance
after Roth told him (Mahathir) that the IMF was there to play a
role should Malaysia need assistance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side did not propose any kind of assistance that the
U.S. government could give to Malaysia to deal with the
situation, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir and Roth also discussed the U.S. military presence in
this region and Mahathir stressed that Malaysia did not want an
increased military presence because it would create anxiety
throughout the region, Mohamed Arshad said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time in the history of Southeast Asia that
things are actually cool and we should not do anything to harm the
civil environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Roth is here to attend the two-day fourth Pacific Dialogue
which ended here Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
