<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Judicial System to Go Through Radical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South African Justice
Minister Dullah Omar has said that judicial system in the country
will be reformed radically this year.
</P>
<P>
Announcing on Monday, Omar said law students could face a
one-year compulsory internship as part of government's plans for
the comprehensive reform of South African legal aid system.
</P>
<P>
Other measures to enhance access to justice through legal aid
include the use of paralegals for nonlitigation work and a
complete redesign of the legal aid board.
</P>
<P>
Draft legislation due before the cabinet this month will
require lay assessors, drawn from the community, to be used in
all lower court cases. Omar described this as a "very drastic
measure".
</P>
<P>
The assessors, who will receive training, will have an equal
say with the magistrate on granting bail, a guilty or not guilty
verdict and on the sentence.
</P>
<P>
To relieve prison overcrowding, the department will extend
significantly its pretrial services project. This aimed to keep
petty criminal out of prisons and those who posed a threat to
society behind bars.
</P>
<P>
There will not be a mass release of petty criminals, but each
case will be assessed individually by the court.
</P>
<P>
Of the 50,000 awaiting-trial prisoners, about 70 percent had
been granted bail but could not pay it, Omar said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a separation of judicial and administrative
functions will be effected so that courts could concentrate on
their judicial responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Justice administration will be decentralized through the
creation of nine provincial justice offices.
</P>
<P>
Legislation will review the witness protection
program with a directorate of witness protection being created
with officers in every province, Omar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
