<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Approves New Foreign Exchange Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has begun a move to
phase out its dual foreign exchange rate regime when most of
government transactions will be carried out according to the
market rate.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Anthony Ani announced on Monday that all
estacode (allowances for officials' foreign trip), travelling
expenses, medical and other bills will be transacted at the rate
of the autonomous foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
But those with the specific approval of the head of state will
continue to enjoy the official rate fixed at one U.S. dollar to
22 Naira, compared to the present market rate of 75 Naira.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, all foreign exchange transactions
carried out by state and local governments, parastatals, oil
mineral producing areas development commission and the petroleum
trust fund shall be conducted at the market rate.
</P>
<P>
However, Ani said transaction pertaining to the transfer of
remittances to embassies abroad, officials of information
ministry residing abroad and other officials performing duties
outside Nigeria would be made at the official rate.
</P>
<P>
The new foreign exchange guidelines which came into effect on
January 10 this year also specified that transactions by the
defense ministry and security agencies as well as items
pertaining to presidential fleet will be remitted at the official
rate.
</P>
<P>
Arms and ammunition and other equipment necessary for the
protection of life and property to be purchased by the police
will be done at the official rate, subject to the approval of the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
Transactions pertaining to the International Football
Federation junior World Cup championship, purchase of outside
broadcasting vans, scoreboards and maintenance of stadia shall be
made at the official rate.
</P>
<P>
The policy equally approved for transactions pertaining to the
funding of Nigeria's external obligations as well as payment for
the modification of the Ajeokuta Steel Complex, the
revitalization of the railway system, X-ray scan equipment for
customs and acquisition of trainer aircraft.
</P>
<P>
With the new arrangement, at least 80 percent of the
government's foreign exchange transaction will be done at the
market rate, according to analysts here.
</P>
<P>
The dual exchange rate system is a sticking point of the
Nigerian government in debt discussions with foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
It is also one of the key areas which have stopped Nigeria
from getting to even the first step needed to pursue debt
rescheduling, a program agreed with the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that a team of the Bretton Woods Financial
Institutions is expected in Nigeria next month to hold
discussions with officials of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The fact that only a few Nigerians have access to buying
foreign exchange at the official rate has also aroused fears of
corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Central Bank Denies Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia has
dismissed reports that a severe shortage of foreign exchange has
hit the country.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted a spokesman of the Central Bank
as saying here on Monday that demand for foreign exchange at the
end of each year and in the first quarter of the year always tend
to pick up.
</P>
<P>
"This, of course, given the liberalized foreign exchange
market, does put pressure for the foreign exchange rate to
depreciate. However, this cannot be interpreted as a critical
shortage of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
"The statistics at the Central Bank show that the
international reserves levels are not that different from those
that prevailed during most of 1997," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the foreign currency deposits held by
commercial banks have increased by almost one-third in the last
four months.
</P>
<P>
"The Bank of Zambia would like to appeal to the business
community and the general public holding foreign exchange with
commercial banks to transact at funds freely," he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently a lot of banks in Lusaka have no foreign exchange to
sell.
</P>
<P>
Early this month local newspaper The Post quoted Sam Equamo,
corporate affairs manager of the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM), as saying that the supply of foreign exchange onto the
market has been constrained by low earnings from copper sales.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM is Zambia's main foreign exchange earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
