<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Another black week has opened in Asian stock exchange markets,
with all stock indices, except that of Seoul, falling on Monday. The
shock wave has attained Russia, South America and Europe. Western
officials no longer hide their fear about the financial crisis while
the economic growth in France this year is expected to be affected.
</P>
<P>
-- Newly published military reports written by French officers,
who served in Rwanda as ``military advisors'' until the end of 1993,
clearly show that France fully engaged in the war in Rwanda on the
side of the Hutus against Tutsi rebels in the months which preceded
the 1994 genocide which killed some 800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The new panic after the stock market crash in Asia on Monday
plunged Europe into torment. The stock exchange index of Hong Kong
and Singapore crashed by falling 8.7 percent, while those of Tokyo
and Bangkok dropped by 2 percent. In Hong Kong, the liquidation of
the Peregrine bank, an establishment emblematic of Asian capitalism,
brought about the fall of the local stocks. Absence of confidence in
the plans to save Asian financial markets also led to a 3.53 percent
fall of the stocks in Frankfurt, 1.35 in London and 1.96 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac will meet Tuesday mayors from 12
suburban cities troubled with insecurity and violence. The mayors
will suggest to Chirac a series of measures to curb urban violence,
including a better supervised distribution of aid to poor families,
the isolation of recidivist deliquents, the development of public
projects and the punishment of all offenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
