<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Central Banks Agree on Joint Research on Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Asian central banks have
agreed to carry out joint research to overcome the region's
financial crisis, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The region's central banks have committed themselves to joint
research to contribute to the systemic health of the regional
economy," Anwar said in his opening remark on the final day of the
two-day Fourth Pacific Dialogue here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar stressed that a common resolve was an imperative and the
global community must act in concert to restore confidence and
rational optimism, warning that unless decisive efforts were taken
to arrest the Asian crisis and the economy was nursed again to
health, the contagion effect would eventually be transmitted to
the global economic system.
</P>
<P>
There is a need for Japan and the United States to step up
their roles in restoring investors' confidence in the prospects of
the Asian economy, Anwar, who is also Malaysia's Finance Minister
and chairman of the two-day dialogue, said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the region had agreed on the need for regional
surveillance and macro-economic coordination.
</P>
<P>
He said the current difficulties have taught the countries in
the region that it was in everybody's interest to alert the
regional community of symptoms of systemic instability wherever
and whenever they occurred.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that the economic crisis confronting the region had
gone beyond mere economics and that unless the situation was
managed wisely and resolved quickly, the social and political
dimensions were going to dominate in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
"The prospect for the growth of dynamic democracies and civil
society in Asia will grow dimmer," he said.
</P>
<P>
If countries in the region were to get out of the morass, they
must first be honest with themselves and be prepared to take tough
measures that would leave no room for doubt about their political
will to reform, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis had compelled governments to accept the need
for transparency and the necessity of making adjustments and
instituting reforms no matter how painful. "They (government) must
swallow the bitter pill," he added.
</P>
<P>
He believed the root of the present crisis was really the
region's failure to provide for a truly humane economy.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the International Monetary Fund (IMF), which was
looked upon as a savior of countries in economic distress, had
not escaped critical scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"Even those who share the belief that the IMF's role is
fundamental to global economic health now dispute its
prescriptions and the manner in which they are being disputed,"
said Anwar.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the World Bank, intentionally or not, had
contributed to the crisis by coining the expression the "East Asia
Economic Miracle" which made Asians to be lulled into complacency.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
