<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Quake Victims to Be Adequately Housed in Five Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGBEI, HEBEI Province, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hebei
provincial government has pledged itself to make every effort to
ensure that all homeless residents in the quake-affected areas
move into temporary housing before January 18.
</P>
<P>
"Our top priority is to put up enough shanties so that our
people would be protected from freezing cold," said Yang Deqing,
secretary of the Zhangjiakou City Party Committee, at a meeting
attended by officials from 37 townships and villages at the quake
epic center last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
the instruction was given by the provincial government, which
is deeply concerned with the well-being of local residents in the
quake areas and is closely following the latest developments
there, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
According to weather forecast, a cold front with strong winds
will hit the quake areas beginning January 18. The temperature on
January 19 will drop to 10 degrees below zero Celsius during
daytime and to a further low of 26 to 23 degrees below zero
Celsius at night.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake relief headquarters in Zhangjiakou has asked
local people to use building materials available including those
sorted out from the debris of the collapsed houses to build
makeshifts, and every family would get 500 yuan in aid.
</P>
<P>
Yang went on to say that the temporary houses should be strong
enough to last at least four or five months.
</P>
<P>
Zhangbei and Shangyi counties in Hebei Province was hit by a
strong earthquake on Saturday. By noon time today, some 30,000
people in the area had moved in to shanties and tents. Officials
said all the 44,000 people in the hardest-hit areas will have a
roof over their head tonight.
</P>
<P>
Today, there is a relatively heavy snowfall in Hebei province,
but it has not affected much in the disaster area.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals have received more patients. Apart from medicines to
provide for the injured, doctors are also distributing among
locals medicine against colds and inflammation. They also caution
people to avoid breathing problems and work to guard against the
possible outbreaks of epidemic meningitis and measles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
