<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Attacks Washington for Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Tehran has strongly attacked the
United States for its "repeat accusations" against Iran, saying
that they would only strengthen the wall of mistrust between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi Monday night
lashed out at the Monday remarks of the U.S. national security
advisor Sandy Berger that Iran poses a threat to the region
considering its policies on terrorism, the Mideast peace and
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Iranian official news agency IRNA Tuesday, the
spokesman said "what the American politicians repeat about Iran
are allegations."
</P>
<P>
"As long as the American Administration does not change its
behavior towards the Islamic Republic and continues to repeat its
routine allegations against Tehran, the bulky wall of mistrust
between Tehran and Washington will continue to exist," Mohammadi
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that certain U.S. political officials and
media have interpreted the recent statements of Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami on relations with the U.S. to their own interests.
</P>
<P>
In his first interview with the Cable News Network (CNN) aired
on Thursday, Khatami called for people-to-people cultural dialog
instead of the government-to-government talks as reported by some
U.S. newspapers.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran "feels no need to have diplomatic ties
with the U.S." since Washington has not changed its policies
towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said Khatami "while emphasizing the dignity and the
might of the Islamic Republic, outlined Iran's rightful stance
and also enumerated the sufferings and pain that the Iranian
nation has endured over many years because of the unfair policies
of the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
The message of Khatami was that Iran will never compromise over
its independence and will not drop its principled stances in the
face of foreign pressure, Mohammadi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
