<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's 1997 Trade Deficit Shrinks Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Israel's 1997 trade deficit
decreased by 23.8 percent over that of the previous year, standing
at 7.894 billion U.S. dollars, The Jerusalem Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the data, published Monday by Israeli Central
Bureau of Statistics, as saying that the 1997 imports fell by 3.2
percent to 28.631 billion dollars, while exports increased by 7.7
percent to 20.737 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decline in imports is the largest since 1985. And the key
declines were in imports of raw materials, investment goods and
consumer products, which indicated a slowdown of Israel's
economy in 1997, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's industrial exports increased by about 16
percent in the high-tech field last year, particularly in
electronics, communications equipment, machinery and supervisory
products.
</P>
<P>
The data also show that Israel now exports more to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) than to Britain or Germany,
making the PNA the second only after the United States in terms of
exports.
</P>
<P>
The PNA imported some 1.57 billion dollars worth of goods from
Israel last year. Most of the imports were funded by grants and
loans from other countries as well as export earnings and income
from Palestinians working in Israel. 
</P>
