<HEADLINE> Interior Minister: New Stage of Crimes Faces Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia is facing a new
stage of organized criminal activities, Russian Interior
Minister Anatoly Kulikov warned on Tuesday, according to
Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Rossiiskiye Vesti,
Kulikov, also Russia's deputy prime minsiter, said although
there is some statistics about a decrease in registered
crimes, experts of the ministry predict a surge of criminal
activities in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"This forecast is backed by the growing number of grave
offenses," the interior minister said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the numbers of bandit assaults at
money-storing facilities, apartment thefts and premeditated
murders are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
"More than one thousand kidnapping cases and 20,000
crimes involving firearms were registered last year. And all this
is just an outward manifestation of the deeply hidden criminal
processs", Kulikov said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the criminal interests now focused on
the process of the transformation of state ownership.
In Kulikov's view, the contributing factors to the
criminal activities are the speedy privatization, and the
inefficient laws.
</P>
<P>
The minister believed that organized crime can be
effectively crashed only by the concerted effort of all
law-enforcement agencies, local and regional authorities,
lawmakers and ordinary citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
