<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Bans Fish Imports from East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
clamped an emergency ban on fish imports from Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania, the East African Standard newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
EU sources attributed the move to health concerns raised over
the prevalence of the cholera epidemic in the three eastern
African countries all bordering on Lake Victoria, the second
largest fresh water lake in the world, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Ryelandt, a senior EU official, was quoted as saying
in Kampala that the ban came into effect on December 23, 1997,
and is expected to be reviewed by the end of February, depending
on the magnitude of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The sanction, which also affected cholera-hit Mozambique, will
be restricted to fresh fish exports, he said, adding frozen and
processed fish products will first undergo cholera tests upon
arrival in Europe at the expense of the exporters, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ban followed a visit to the region by EU health inspectors
during the first three weeks of December.
</P>
<P>
The cholera outbreak caused by heavy rains, has claimed over
1,000 lives since November in Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Ryelandt said the EU has asked the three east African
countries to meet the EU's set quality standards in fish exports
up to June, otherwise, their fish will be permanently banned from
Europe.
</P>
<P>
The EU has repeatedly warned the three states to upgrade
sanitary operation for fish destined to Europe, charging that
fish from the region has a high level of bacteria infections due
to poor handling.
</P>
<P>
EU inspectors visiting east Africa in May last year said that
airports there lacked cold storage facilities suitable for fish
while landing sites also lacked sanitary facilities.
</P>
<P>
The EU is ready to help the three countries in upgrading
sanitary facilities, provided they present their budgets in time
to escape the June deadline, Ryelandt said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
