<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Woeful Year for Thailand's Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Investors on the Stock Exchange
of Thailand (SET) were simply unable to take a breath of relief
last year as the SET index kept falling almost all year round.
</P>
<P>
The SET index fell 55.18 percent in the entire 1997, reflecting
the extent of the country's macroeconomic slump, the turmoil in
the financial sector and the collapse of the baht.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 began with the SET opening at 831.57 points, and
closing at 372.69 points, losing 458.88 points, or a staggering
55.18 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SET index peaked for the year on January 22, at 858.97
points, and the low came on December 26, when the market closed at
357.13.
</P>
<P>
The total trade on the market last year was worth about 930
billion baht, equal to an average daily turnover of 3.76 billion
baht, a stark drop from the 1996 total volume of 1,300 billion
baht, or 5.34 billion baht per day.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors' transactions accounted for 43.31 percent of
the total trading value last year, worth 805 billion baht.
</P>
<P>
In the year, SET regulators initiated several changes to
bolster supervision and monitoring systems, internal control and
risk management among listed members.
</P>
<P>
A major change was the raising of trading ceiling and floor
prices on the main board by 10 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
A "circuit-breaker" system was also introduced to slow trading
in times of high volatility. Under this system, if the index drops
more than 100 percent from the pervious day's close, trading is
halted for one hour, and a drop of more than 200 percent will see
the market closed for the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
Regulations were also made to improve the quality of listed
firms. Relaxed listing requirements for provincial companies were
eliminated, and only firms with established track records could be
accepted. Minimum capital and financial performance requirements
for new applicants were also raised.
</P>
<P>
In spite of these changes, a 17.2 billion U.S. dollar bailout
package arranged by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), and a
more popular Democrats-led coalition government, which came to
office in early November, investors' confidence did not see any
improvement late last year or early this year.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the SET index has kept last year's falling
trend, losing another 33.52 points, or 9 percent in just six
trading days from the 1997 year-end level.
</P>
<P>
The SET index kept its steady slide in 1997 along with the
baht, which has suffered a de factor devaluation since its
floating on July 2, from 25.79 baht per U.S. dollar on the eve of
the floating to 47.286 baht at year-end, losing 83.35 percent of
its value in only six months.
</P>
<P>
Other factors which had adverse impact on the SET include the
suspension by the government of 58 ailing finance companies, of
which 56 were subsequently closed down in December, and the
monetary crises in other countries in Asia, such as those in the
Philippines, Indonesia, Malaysia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
On Monday the baht again hit an all-time low, closing at 56.40
baht to the U.S. dollar in local market, and at 56.10 baht in
foreign market.
</P>
<P>
It means that with 56.10 baht, which are now worth one U.S.
dollar, a buyer could have got 2.175 dollars before the floating.
</P>
<P>
It seems certain that with the various adverse factors in the
country and the region, the free fall of the SET index and the
baht will continue.
</P>
<P>
One worrying element is the strict austerity conditions set by
the IMF when it offered its bailout program for Thailand in August
1997.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates, increased taxes and low government
spending, as required by the IMF for Thailand's right to draw
money from the program, will now do more harm than good to the
Thai economy, following the wide-spread monetary turmoil across
East and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has decided to negotiate with the IMF later
this month for better terms under changed circumstances, and it
has also called for financial assistance from the United States
and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Without a halt in the regional financial crisis and more
assistance from the international community, the Thai economy,
including the SET and the baht, will get worse before it gets
better, with a possible bottoming out toward the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
