<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Banks Urged to Check Currency Volatility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Asian central banks should
consider establishing a fund to check currency fluctuations in the
region, American International Group, Inc. (AIG) chairman and
chief executive officer Maurice Greenberg said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"What I'm talking about is a fund that regional central banks
can use to moderate excessive currency fluctuations," he told
reporters on the sidelines of the two-day Fourth Pacific Dialogue
which ended here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Greenberg, who attended the dialogue, described attacks on
currencies as "very destructive" and said they must be blunted to
prevent them from wrecking any country's currency.
</P>
<P>
"It's one thing that free market should flourish but you also
have to prevent the type of attacks that can be very destructive,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Speculative attacks on regional currencies such as the Thai
baht, the Indonesian rupiah, the Malaysian ringgit and the Korean
won have resulted in the significant depreciation of these
currencies against the U.S. dollar, causing the region to suffer
its worst economic and financial turmoil since last July.
</P>
<P>
Greenberg was of the view that the assistance of the
International Monetary Fund, which has given aid to Indonesia,
Thailand and South Korea, should be sought as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
AIG, an American insurance conglomerate, will announce details
of its new infrastructure fund of about 2 billion U.S. dollars
Wednesday in Singapore for investments throughout the region,
Greenberg said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
