<HEADLINE> Russian Foreign Policy Serves State Interests: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The aim of the Russian foreign
policy is and will continue to be the protection of national
interests without sliding down to confrontation, Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
In an article "Integration Processes -- Main Road For
Humanity," Primakov said that the protection of Russia's state
interests is going on in various directions, but it will not
return to the "cold war," the Itar-Tass new agency reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the results of Russian's foreign policy in 1997, the
foreign minister said the diversification of Russia's foreign
political activities proved to be effective, and the course chosen
proved to be correct.
</P>
<P>
Primakov believed that Russia's membership of the Group of
Eight was one of the main accomplishments of its foreign policy in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Russia has also made headway in developing relations with the
Association of South-East Asian Nations (ASEAN), and it is soon to
be admitted to the Asia-Pacific Economic Community, he added.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on partnership with the European Union has come
into force, Primakov continued. Russia has taken part in 17
peace-keeping operations, which showed the role played by Russia
on a global level.
</P>
<P>
"We have a real forecast saying that the world is moving
towards a multi-polar structure," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
On relations with the United States, the minister said, "The
rapprochement of our positions with those of the United States is
going on on the basis of equality, mutual protection and the
recognition of the right of each of the parties to protect its
interests, but without sliding down to confrontation."
</P>
<P>
In the article, Primakov also stressed the development in
consolidating relations within the Commonwealth of Independent
States, in particular with Belarus and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
