<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Down in Kenya Despite Election Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's inflation rate
continued to drop in December, reflecting a sustained economic
stability although election fever culminated in at that time.
</P>
<P>
The three-months annualized inflation eased to 2.7 percent in
December from 5.5 percent in November, according to the January
edition of the Monthly Economic Review issued by the Central Bank
of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
While, the average annual inflation marginally fell to 11.2
percent from 11.4 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The overall month-on-month inflation stood at 8.3 percent in
December, almost the same level as that recorded in November,
said the review.
</P>
<P>
The underlying inflation also eased, with the three-month
annualized inflation dropping to 6.2 percent in December from
10.8 percent in November, while the underlying average annual
inflation eased to 6.6 percent from 7.1 percent during the
period.
</P>
<P>
The decline is largely due to a slower expansion of broad
money supply than in the past and the relatively stable Shilling
exchange rate last month, said the review.
</P>
<P>
"A significant factor behind the decline in inflation was the
sustained slower expansion in money supply that restrained
aggregate demand to levels consistent with the anticipated GDP
growth in 1997," said the review.
</P>
<P>
"The less volatile exchange rate in the month also helped to
contain the inflationary pressures implicit in imports and in
consumer items such as health, clothing and footwear," it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the underlying month-on-month inflation edged up to
5.4 percent in December compared with 5.3 percent in the previous
month. Underlying inflation excludes "transitory" factors which
are affect inflation on a short term.
</P>
<P>
The review also predicted that the declining trend in
inflation is to continue in the months ahead because appropriate
macro economic policies are in place, in addition to the expected
restoration of investors' confidence in Kenya's economy.
</P>
<P>
"To enhance the effectiveness of tight monetary policy on
inflation, a more restrained fiscal policy should be pursued.
The fiscal policy should ensure that the budget deficit does
not exceed 1.7 percent of GDP by the end of 1997/98," it noted.
</P>
<P>
"This requires the government revenue collection system to be
strengthened further," said the review. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
