<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Studying Public's Awareness of Science in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Although most Chinese respect
scientists, the general public's knowledge of science remains
quite low, according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
It showed that scientists are among the most respected people
in China, ahead of doctors and government officials, and that 44.4
percent of those who responded want their children to become
scientists.
</P>
<P>
The study, which covered 29 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions, was done by the China Association for Science
and Technology, the State Science and Technology Commission, and
the Institute of Chinese Popular Science.
</P>
<P>
This respect for scientists does not, however, help the public
in their knowledge of science, says Li Daguang of the Institute of
Chinese Popular Science.
</P>
<P>
The study also contained some basic questions about physics,
biology, medicine, and geography, closely related to people's
daily lives, and the results, when compared with a similar survey
in the United States, were poor for most of the questions.
</P>
<P>
However, 65.7 percent of those responding think that man
evolved from the anthropoid ape, a greater number than for their
American counterparts, and this shows a big cultural difference
between China and the western countries, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of those surveyed said that they are concerned
about environmental problems, but only 10.5 percent know that the
major hole of the ozone layer is over the South Pole, and 49.8
percent seemed unaware of the causes of ozone depletion.
</P>
<P>
Chinese show as much interest as Americans in new scientific
developments, but only 24.8 percent of the Chinese are interested
in developments in medical science, compared with 69 percent in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that about 78 percent of the Chinese
haven't visited museums or scientific and technological
exhibitions in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Li said that males performed better than females, and that the
higher the education level of the respondent, the higher his or
her scientific awareness.
</P>
<P>
"So increasing education is the only way to increase public
scientific awareness," he concludes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Build Double-dipping Tirecord Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will start
building a double-dipping tirecord plant in Port Elizabeth next
month.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the building of the new 45-million Rand
(nine million U.S. Dollars) plant, to be called Industryre, the
first ever in southern Africa, was made Monday by Francois de
Selliers, Managing Director of Industex, South Africa's largest
technical textile manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed a good news for locgl tyre
manufacturers which have had to import double-dipped fabric which
forces them to be less competitive, cost wise, on the export
market.
</P>
<P>
Once up and running, the plant will produce 100 meters of
dipped tirecord a minute, a capacity of at least 15,000 tons per
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new plant will create approximately 130 jobs by year 2002
with the construction of the unit taking approximately 15 months.
This number of jobs could increase to over 200 by 2005 if the
venture is as successful as foreseen.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the new dipping complex plant is due to start
next month and first production should begin by March or April
next year.
</P>
<P>
At present the three Port Elizabeth-based tyre companies have
single dipping facilities. Industyre's dipping plant would
provide higher quality material at a cheaper price than fabric
presently imported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
