<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Military Officer Meets Former U.S. Military Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Chairman of China's
Central Military Commission Zhang Wannian said here today that
both China and the United States have a will to improve the
development of relations between the two countries and their armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said he held a positive attitude toward the development
of such ties.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's remarks were made at a meeting with William Perry,
former U.S. Secretary of Defense, and a delegation led by him.
</P>
<P>
The vice-chairman highly praised efforts by Perry and other
visitors in promoting military-to-military exchanges and
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to the
United States in October scored great success.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President
Bill Clinton reached agreement on jointly building a constructive
strategic partnership oriented toward the 21st century between
China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
This is a major contribution to world peace, stability and
prosperity in the new century, Zhang said, adding that it also
marked a new phase of development in Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
Zhang told his U.S. visitors that Taiwan is the most important
and sensitive issue affecting the healthy development of
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral ties would stablize and advance if the Taiwan issue
can be properly settled, Zhang said. Otherwise, ties could be
harmed and even go backwards, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed his hope that the United States would abide
conscientiously by the principles enshrined in the three
Sino-U.S. joint communiques and deal with the Taiwan issue in a
proper way.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also briefed the U.S. guests on China's domestic
situation.
</P>
<P>
Perry said that maintaining a strategic partnership between the
two sides is crucial to improving regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
The two sides can handle the existing problems between the two
countries through constructive and positive consultation, Perry
said, in hopes that the relations between the two countries and
the military-to-military relations can move forward in a healthy
and stable way.
</P>
<P>
Perry showed concern to the people in north China's Hebei
Province struck by a severe earthquake and aftershocks, and spoke
highly of the timely and positive efforts of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army in providing disaster relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
