<HEADLINE> Australian Tourism to Double Despite Asia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Australian Acting Prime
Minister Tim Fischer said Tuesday that he is confident the number
of overseas visitors to Australia will double despite an Asian
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"And whilst yes, numbers from Korea and other places are
dropping, that does not mean there's not a great capability to
attract eco-tourists and other tourists from other parts of the
world," Fischer told journalists in the northern state of New
South Wales.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press quoted Fischer as saying at the
World Heritage Rainforest Center, which he opened in the state,
that attractions such as rainforests and other forms of
eco-tourism would help counteract the loss of tourists to more
traditional tourist centers visited by Asians.
</P>
<P>
"There is a growing market for eco-tourism of which I think
we've only just begun to scratch the potential," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"The tourism industry is not immune to the tougher market
conditions for inbound Asian tourists," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That does not mean that there's not a bold future for the
tourist industry," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said 11 of the globe's 400 world heritage areas in Australia
and eco-tourism offer the country an opportunity to maximize its
competitive advantage growing on the natural features and the
unique flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of the Australian dollar against the U.S.
dollar also makes tour in Australia cheaper for tourists from
North America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Australia expects tourists from the United States, Europe and
China would increase and thus counteract the loss of tourists from
Japan, Korea and some other Asian countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
