<HEADLINE> Iran's Human Rights Body Opposes Trial of French </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Human Rights
Commission (IHCR) has announced its support for a French author,
who is on trial for his controversial book on Israel as Tehran
radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This stance of IHCR came in a message to Roger Garaudi, a
French professor and philosopher, the author of the book "Les
Mythes Fondeteurs de la Politique Israelienne" (Founding Myths of
Israeli Politics), published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He has been on trial since last Thursday in Paris for denying
the existence of gas chambers for the extermination of Jews in
World War II in the book. He also said that the extermination of 6
million Jews during the war by the Nazis is a myth used to justify
everything Israel has demanded and obtained from Palestine,
according to the radio report.
</P>
<P>
In the message sent to Garaudi Monday, the IHRC said that the
trial is bringing freedom of speech and thought to trial.
</P>
<P>
The commission noted that the trial of Garaudi is a
demonstration of disrespect and non-conformity to the practice of
freedom of speech in association with a scholar who intends to
make public his research works.
</P>
<P>
Iran does not recognize the Israeli government for Israel's
occupation of Arab land, particularly Jerusalem, a place
considered as one of the holiest sites for the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The IHRC was established in 1995 with an aim to defend the
Iranian authorities over human rights issues. The commission has
repeatedly rejected Western accusation of Iran's human rights
abuses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0217 </DOCNO>
