<HEADLINE> Philippines Denies Scrapping Plane Purchase Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines, the
country's flag carrier, Tuesday denied reports that it has
canceled the purchase of four Boeing planes due to the currency
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Avelina Zapanta, PAL senior vice president for sales and
services, said that the company is expecting four Boeing planes to
be delivered within the year while the remaining four should come
by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Zapanta noted that the near completion of its 4 billion U.S.
dollars modernization program with the delivery of the eight
Boeing 747s by late 1999.
</P>
<P>
Despite the grave currency situation, PAL had coped well with
the lingering crisis, Zapanta said.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis has not had much effect on the once-beleaguered
airline because 80 percent of its reserves come from international
operations, we are definitely hedged against the currency
depreciation," Zapanta said.
</P>
<P>
The impact, however, would be on PAL's foreign debt, he said.
</P>
<P>
To finance its expansion, PAL used offshore borrowings which
prior to the peso devaluation entailed lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Zapanta said the 70 percent fall of the peso against the dollar
has raised PAL's costs by 10 to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The airlines' modernization program calls for 36 new aircraft
-- 28 from Airbus Industrie in France and eight from the
Seattle-based Boeing. The program aims to arm PAL with the
youngest fleet among Asian carriers, Zapanta said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
