<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Quake Victims Move into Tents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGBEI (Hebei), January 13 (Xinhua) -- "I was playing outside
when my house suddenly collapsed with a loud crash," recalled
13-year-old Wu Tianjiang, waiting in line Tuesday for a relief
cotton-padded overcoat and a cotton blanket.
</P>
<P>
Wu lives in Luanshishan Village, Dahe Township, one of the most
badly stricken villages by Saturday's earthquake in Zhangbei and
Shangyi counties of north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
"I'm dreaming of a home so that my parents and I can have a
sweet sleep," said Wu, exhausted after having no comfortable sleep
for three nights.
</P>
<P>
A small shed coated with cotton quilts became the shelter for
the Wu family since the Jan. 10 earthquake. The four-member family
has to keep warm by a stove at the shed's entry.
</P>
<P>
The other 70 families in Luanshishan Village have been leading
similar lives these days. Some villagers who did not have sheds
are sharing with neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Several severely damaged villages in Zhangbei County are nearly
1,600 meters above sea level. Night-time temperatures are often 20
degrees below zero Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
"Heaven is quite cooperative these days," said Gao Ying from
Wenshulugou Village of Dahe Township. "The temperature could drop
to minus 27 to 28 degrees at night in former years." Gao was
worried that possible snowfall would make things worse.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers from the Beijing Military Area Command are helping
villagers build cotton tents. The 1.5-meter-thick frozen ground
makes digging very difficult, said Commander Liu Jie. But he said
that soldiers would work harder to ensure that more villagers
could move into tents. Liu's company had finished putting up 10
cotton tents in half a day.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 military cotton tents have been pitched for
villagers in Dahe Township with each tent sheltering 25
people. More than 1,600 similar tents have been transported to
Zhangbei County, with more on the way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
