<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Said to Hit Australia in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia faces a blowout in
interest rates and unemployment and an economic recession at the
start of the next century as a result of the Asian meltdown, the
country's major economic forecaster warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There is little Australia could do to avoid being dragged down
by the Asian turmoil, the National Institute of Economic and
Industry Research told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
The institute, Australia's largest independent economic
forecaster, said there is little hope of avoiding an economic
downturn in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
"The real concern is what will happen around 2000. The crisis
has still got a long way to go (and) a lot of the problems are
beyond Australia's policy control," said Tim Toohey, the
institute's senior economist.
</P>
<P>
Toohey's comments are in contrast to beliefs that Australia's
strong domestic demand would provide a buffer against the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that as Australia's international trade
position weakens, the current extremely low interest rates are
likely to almost double, leaving a significant portion of the
population laboring under a large amount of debt.
</P>
<P>
More personal debt would mean less spending, causing companies
to lay off staff and increasing unemployment to above 11 percent
by 2002 from the current 8.5 percent, Toohey predicted.
</P>
<P>
He said a slowdown in western economies after year 2000 has
been on the cards for several years, but would be severely
exacerbated if Asian economies do not quickly deregulate and
reorganize themselves.
</P>
<P>
But he recommended that Australia continue to encourage reform
and deregulation in Asian economies, avoid subsidizing faltering
companies, and fight the systemic corruption in many Asian
economies.
</P>
<P>
The situation would also be affected by changes in the U.S. and
Chinese economies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Tourism Programs Offered to Visitors to Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- To attract more Chinese and
overseas visitors to Guilin, a leading scenic site in the country,
a series of new historical and cultural sites and facilities have
been repaired in the city.
</P>
<P>
The famous resort city of Guilin, located in southwest China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, reputedly has the "most
beautiful rivers and mountains in the world."
</P>
<P>
The 1998 tourism program will offer opportunities to share not
only the Guilin's picturesque natural scenery with visitors, but
also the idyllic countryside, said Huang Jiacheng, director of the
city's tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the city receives more than 400,000 overseas
tourists and 10 million domestic visitors every year due to
improvements in tourism facilities and transportation.
</P>
<P>
This year Guilin will sponsor several important outdoor
activities such as rafting along the scenic Lijiang River during
the summer-autumn period, cycling and hiking.
</P>
<P>
The city also will provide a series of traditional and new
scenic spots such as the Jingjiang Mausoleum and Miao and Yao
villages as well as nine major tourism routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
