<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sends Novel New Year's Greetings to Workers in Need </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- You Jianmin, a 44-year-old
employee of a Shanghai electronics company, was moved to tears,
when local trade union officials handed her relief funds with
their new year's greetings.
</P>
<P>
You suffers from epilepsy and her husband has a disability as
well, but fortunately the couple were one of several hundred
families in need of financial aid that officials of the Shanghai
Trade Union Council, led by President Bao Xinbao, hadn't
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
The group sent them holiday greetings along with the money,
around New Year's Day. The Shanghai municipal government plans to
spend 90 million yuan on these workers around New Year's Day and
Spring Festival this year.
</P>
<P>
A number of Shanghai's workers are in similar straits. In
addition to those in poor health or with heavy family burdens,
there are those laid off because of problems in the factory.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the municipality has worked to maintain a minimum
wage and living standard that guarantees the basic needs of its
residents, and even has a computer network that covers 500,000 of
these people.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the authorities provide grain and edible oil at a
low cost and stipends for students in need. Each holiday, local
officials, from municipal leaders to factory heads, go to the
homes of needy workers and extend their greetings. Last year,
officials in Shanghai visited 500,000 households.
</P>
<P>
Poverty-relief funds and charitable foundations are the main
source of help for needy families. These organizations now have in
excess of 400 million yuan, which comes from government
allocations, the service industry, and individual donations.
</P>
<P>
Various other groups in Shanghai have also begun to join the
aid-the-poor effort. Some 15 local hospitals began providing
medical cards for people in need last year, offering them free
medical care.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
