<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qaidam Basin Playing Major Role in China's Oil Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Qaidam Basin oilfield in
northwest China's Qinghai province produced 1.6 million tons of
oil in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Qaidam Basin on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau has 4.2 billion
tons of proven reserves, according to a provincial petroleum
administration official.
</P>
<P>
Qaidam also has 150 billion cu.m. of proven gas reserves,
fourth largest in China, after Sichuan, Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia, and
Tarim.
</P>
<P>
The 24 square kilomater Qinghai oilfield, which was first
developed in 1954, has produced 15.5 million tons of crude oil and
refined nearly eight million tons of them. Nearly a billion yuan
has been spent on oil and gas exploration, increasing reserves by
40 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
The China National Petroleum Corporation, Qinghai Provincial
Government, and the US's Amoco will develop large chemical
projects to produce chloride, caustic soda, synthetic ammonia, and
urea, in Golmud in the middle of the Qaidam Basin, during the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Two gas pipes with a combined length of nearly 300 kilometers
and a gas-powered station with an installed capacity of 16,000
kilowatts are now in operation. A third 280-km gas pipe linking
the Qinghai Petroleum Administration and Dunhuang in Gansu
Province and a project of the Golmud Oil Refinery, which will
produce 100,000 tons of methanol annually, will be launched in
1999.
</P>
<P>
The Qaidam basin is a key oil and gas region for China's
National Petroleum Corporation, and will have an annual oil output
of three million tons by the year 2000, and ten million tons by
2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
