<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Allied Commander Meets Croatian Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zagreb, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Wesly Clark, Supreme Allied
Commander in NATO, held talks with Croatian Defense Minister
Gojko Susak on regional security, cooperation between Croatia
and NATO and especially cooperation between Croatia and the
NATO-led Multi-national Stablization Force (SFOR) Monday.
</P>
<P>
Clark arrived here the same day for his first visit to Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Under the NATO-Croatia cooperation agreement, Croatia allows
SFOR to use Split and Porec, and station its rear-services in the
ports.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Croatia also allows SFOR to use its air space and
roads to transport troops, military equipments and materials to
Bosnia-Hezegovina, and to base its headquarters in Zagreb, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Clark said NATO and SFOR were looking
forward to the implementation by Croatia of all the provisions
stipulated in the Dayton Accord.
</P>
<P>
On Croatia's participation in NATO's Partnership for Peace
program, Clark said Susak mentioned the subject during the talks,
but NATO, despite its notice of Croatia's desire, had until now
taken no clear position.
</P>
<P>
Susak also announced that he will visit the U.S. on the 30th of
this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
