<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Finance Minsiter Urged for Talks with IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
Governor Micah Cheserem has urged new Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae to re-open talks with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) which cut a key aid package to Kenya last year.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between Kenya and IMF, and a three-year
205-million-Dollar aid package were suspended on July 31 since
the latter doubted that the Kenyan government had the
determination to end corruption.
</P>
<P>
Chesrem said: "Talks with the IMF and World Bank and other
donors will lead to availability of funding needed to finance
infrastructure, repair and upgrading of roads. We do not have
that money."
</P>
<P>
Nyachae, who was appointed last week, would face a shortage of
money necessary for outstanding development projects, local press
reports quoted Cheserem as saying today.
</P>
<P>
A resumption of IMF lending is expected to also release more
funds from the World Bank and bilateral donors to the eastern
African country.
</P>
<P>
As Finance Minister, Nyachae is the leader in economic policy
and the Central Bank will continue its advisory role in helping
him to manage the economy, Cheserem added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports said an IMF team is set to visit Kenya on
February 9 to resume talks with Nyachae on the suspended loan
program under Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
An experienced and forceful Nyachae has been widely regarded
in the local business community as a command economy enthusiast
and a supporter of intervention.
</P>
<P>
At the handing over ceremony last week, Nyachae said he has
initiated reforms in agriculture, particularly in the tea,
coffee, and cereals industries, but he said he had no intention
to drastically change the economic programs launched by his
predecessor Musalia Mudavadi.
</P>
<P>
Kenya and IMF agreed in September on measures to "strengthen
management of the energy sector, safeguard the independence of
the KRA, ensure that Anti-Corruption Authority would be
independent and establish accountability for past financial
infractions."
</P>
<P>
The IMF allowed the first year's agreement to lapse with the
disbursement of the initial 37-million-Dollar slice soon after
the three-year ESAF loan package was signed in April 1995. Kenya
failed to convince the IMF to release the second
37-million-Dollar loan which was lost.
</P>
<P>
Hopes now hinge on salvaging the remaining 148 million Dollars
and accompanying structural adjustment credits from the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
New IMF guidelines on corruption say staff can recommend
halting a loan if they suspect poor governance is hurting
economic performance or threatening implementation of an IMF
refrom plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
