<HEADLINE> Iran Denies President's Speech as Response to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran has strongly rejected the
reports that the interview of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
with the Cable News Network (CNN) was a response to Washington's
message for government-to-government dialog.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA Tuesday quoted the
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi as saying Monday that
Khatami's interview was an initiative for opening up a dialog
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Such an initiative could not, under any circumstances, be
regarded as a reply to any U.S. message," Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "according to the same old procedure and
protocol any exchange of notes between the Islamic Republic of
Iran and the United States has been conducted through the
U.S. interest office at the Swiss embassy in Tehran and that
Iran has always dispatched its clear responses through the
same channel."
</P>
<P>
Washington Post reported Friday that the U.S. Administration
secretly made a proposal to the Iranian government for
face-to-face talks.
</P>
<P>
The report did not give details about Washington's proposal,
but saying that the proposal was raised in a letter to the
Iranian government through the U.S. interest office at the Swiss
embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Many western media said that Khatami's interview with CNN
broadcast Thursday was a response to the U.S. proposal and some
U.S. officials considered Khatami's call for cultural dialog as "a
kind of public answer" to Washington's message.
</P>
<P>
In his first address to the "great American people," Khatami
called for exchanges between Iranian and American professors,
writers, scholars, artists, journalists and tourists, but
stressing that Iran "feels no need to have diplomatic ties with
the U.S." since Washington has not changed its attitude towards
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Observers and diplomats here said that Khatami's remark on
need for Iran to have ties with the U.S. indicated many
hurdles still exist on the way for a possible rapprochement
between the two sworn enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
