<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Makes Rules on of Chinese Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province recently followed the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
and Hebei Province when it passed a regional law to standardize
the use of Chinese language characters.
</P>
<P>
The six-chapter law stipulates that the use of outmoded
characters on ads or shop signs will be considered illegal as of
March 1, and units and individuals are being told to use standard
Chinese for public functions.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants, teachers, and people working in the service
trade will be asked to pass a Putonghua (Standard Chinese) test
before they can work, according to the new regulation.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts say that they spent five years working on the
regulation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
