<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Considers Cuts in Corn Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Agriculture is considering sharply lowering tariffs on yellow corn
imports as a "temporary relief" to the livestock industry being
battered by the financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The department will likely reduce corn tariff rates to a low of
3 percent to save the livestock industry, Assistant Agriculture
Secretary Marinela Castillo said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country now imposes tariffs ranging from 35 to 80 percent
on yellow corn imports. Certain quotas are allowed at a minimum 35
percent but the rest has to be imported at higher tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The livestock industry's production gains have been on a
downhill due to the currency crisis sweeping Asia since July 1997.
The crisis has sent interest rates and production cost
skyrocketing.
</P>
<P>
Industry leaders projected that livestock production for 1998
would drop by a minimum of 15 percent to a maximum of 25 percent,
surpassing the 10 percent annual growth made in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
Castillo said that there is an immediate need to cushion the
impact of the financial turmoil going on in the region on the
country's livestock industry by giving temporary relief through
the reduction of tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
According to Castillo, the government's recommendation is to
cut the corn tariff rates to 3 percent though the industry's
preference is a reduction to the zero level.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Agriculture is going to draft its
recommendation for submission to the Department of Justice, which
will decide whether the measure is legal in view of the existing
requirements of the World Trade Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
