<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Big Aftershocks Expected in Zhangbei, Shangyi Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- No earthquakes exceeding
Saturday's 6.2 temblor are expected to strike the Zhangbei and
Shangyi areas soon, the State Seismological Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
But the bureau didn't rule out the possibility of mid-magnitude
aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
By 6 a.m. today, 349 aftershocks had occurred in the region, 10
of which were above 4.0 on the Richter scale. The largest
aftershock so far measured 4.6, according to the State
Seismological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Aftershocks occur in various forms, said Ding Jianhai, a
researcher with the Earthquake Analysis and Prediction Center
under the State Seismological Bureau. They may cease immediately
after the earthquake or continue for a long period of time, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Aftershocks of the Tangshan Earthquake in 1976, which claimed
hundreds of thousands of lives, can still be detected, he said.
</P>
<P>
"An earthquake is the adjustment of the Earth's inner
structure, which needs time to reach a balance, so it is quite
natural for several mid-magnitude aftershocks to occur in this
time period," Ding said.
</P>
<P>
Gao Xu, deputy director of the Beijing Municipal Seismological
Bureau, said that no detectable earthquake has occurred in the
capital since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Even if strong aftershocks occur in the quake-affected regions
around Zhangjiakou, it will not pose threats to the capital," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter scale struck
the Zhangbei and Shangyi regions in north China's Hebei Province,
killing 50 people and leveling 103,000 houses. Emergency relief
work is under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
