<HEADLINE> Asian Currency Crisis May Cut Australian Coal Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The current Asian currency
crisis is likely to push down the price of Australian coal exports
despite continuing strong demand, an Australian local mineral
council said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Most people have been expecting some sort of price fall,"
Denis Porter, acting executive director of the New South Wales
(state) Minerals Council told Australian Broadcasting Corporation
Radio.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a strong demand for energy out there in the
Asian region, a strong demand for coal," he said. "We would expect
to see some growth continuing, although I think the growth will be
trimmed substantially in a number of countries."
</P>
<P>
Representatives of major Australian companies were in Japan
this week negotiating the price of thermal coal.
</P>
<P>
Porter said contracts were negotiated in American dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar has devalued against the U.S. dollar and
this is good for exporters, who get more Australian dollars back
for every U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"So if the Australian dollar stays down that's good news for us
and it would help us withstand a fall, if there were to be a fall,
in the U.S. dollar price of coal," he said.  
</P>
