<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expert Says It's Not Bigfoot, It's Just Big Bears (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The legendary bigfoot, or yeti,
of the Himalayan mountains could simply be a brown bear, according
to one Chinese wildlife expert.
</P>
<P>
Liu Wulin, the head of the Forestry Department's Wildlife
Protection Office in the Tibet Autonomous Region, says that the
hides and bones they have that are supposed to be bigfoot are
clearly from some beast.
</P>
<P>
After more than ten years' search for the creature in Medong,
Gyirong, Nangxian, Tingri, and Yadong counties, Liu is certain
that the footprints he's seen that are 20 to 30 centimeters long
and similar to those of human beings, were made by brown bears.
</P>
<P>
"It must be bears leaving those marks that lack an arch, but
the pads really resemble man's," Liu says. The brown bear is an
endangered species under strict protection. It usually lives in
caves 3,500 meters above sea level in northern Tibet, according to
Liu, who is in charge of the Lhasa branch of the Administrative
Office for the Import and Export of Endangered Species.
</P>
<P>
In Tibetan legend, female bears liked harassing women while
male bears love to kidnap attractive women.
</P>
<P>
In fact, dozens of brown bears from the northern Tibetan
prairies gather in natural caves in Amdo County in the
summertime. They go into a cave and leave out of it in a
queue. Scientists say that this bear convention remains an
inexplicable mystery.
</P>
<P>
But, local people confuse the brown bear with bigfoot, and
don't even want to look at the beast because of the legend. It is
supposed that the brown bear has a red nose, mouth, and hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
