<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Exports Do Well Despite Asia's Financial Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's exports have
successfully weathered Southeast Asia's financial turmoil to hit a
new high in 1997, according to a senior municipal official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics record 14.7 billion U.S. dollars in exports for
1997, up 11.2 percent over the previous year and representing the
sixth year of sustained growth.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhu Xiaoming, head of the municipal foreign trade and
economic commission, said it may be difficult for Shanghai to
maintain its momentum this year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign financial problems, especially in Japan and the
Republic of Korea, have had negative effects on Shanghai's
exports, he said, because 34 percent of its trade is with these
two countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is time to make an overall structural reform in the city's
foreign trade sector to alleviate the problem," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
The planned restructuring will emphasize high-value-added and
high-technology exports.
</P>
<P>
In exploring overseas export markets, Zhu said that -- apart
from furthering efforts in Japan, North America and European
countries -- attempts also will be made in South Africa, Latin
America and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Shanghai has worked out preferential policies to
encourage the city's large companies to enhance their overseas
presence, especially in South Africa and Southeast Asia, according
to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He added that Shanghai will give priority to developing exports
of such international services as tourism, transportation,
contracted projects, retail commerce and consultation.
</P>
<P>
The city has been listed by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation as a pilot in developing international
service trade, Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
