<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Expert Says It's Not Bigfoot, It's Just Big Bears (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But, the hair Liu got in one village convinced him that it was
just brown bear's.
</P>
<P>
In the Himalayas, there are said to be many abominable snowmen,
or yetis, but, again, Liu says he thinks the creatures, which are
described as being like tall human beings, are just white-haired
bears.
</P>
<P>
"The bears usually hibernate in winter, but some go looking for
food below the snow line," Liu explains, and brown bears' hair can
turn grey or white.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese encyclopedia, the 'Cihai', calls a type of
white-and-black bear as the newly-discovered Tibetan panda, and
the Encyclopedia Britannica has a similar description, which Liu
insists is a mistake.
</P>
<P>
"Even if the bigfoot, or yeti, did exist, it would be doomed to
extinction because of its tiny population and inbreeding," Liu
explained.
</P>
<P>
Around the globe, bigfoot is listed as one of four major
mysteries, in the company of UFOs (unidentified flying objects),
the Loch Ness monster, and the Bermuda Triangle.
</P>
<P>
One Tibetan theologian and poet of the 11th century was the
first to record description of the creature, and the stories have
been kept alive since the 1950s, when nearby Nepal opened its
doors to tourists.
</P>
<P>
In recent decades, many teams of searchers have gone around
looking for the creature, but no one has ever provided any solid
proof to support the belief that these are humans' close relative.
</P>
<P>
In fact, there are hardly any photos, just some
suspicious-looking footmarks, but, in the meantime, locals repeat
the stories about sightings of bigfoot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen's Economy Developing Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The economy in Shenzhen,
China's leading special economic zone, developed steadily in 1997
with its focus on reforming state-owned enterprises and opening to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province statistics show that the city's gross
domestic product (GDP) in 1997 increased by 16 percent to 113
billion yuan (14.1 billion U.S. dollars), and its industrial
output was up 17.5 percent to 125.5 billion yuan (15.7 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The production value of 18 major company groups accounted for
56.7 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
New, high-technology industries in telecommunications, new
materials and biological engineering have developed rapidly with
the value of their products topping 47.4 billion yuan (5.9 billion
U.S. dollars). That figure was 35 percent of the city's total
industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city invested 39 billion yuan (4.87
billion U.S. dollars) in fixed assets, an increase of 19.1 percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The asset-to-liability ratio of the city's state-owned
enterprises has dropped from 70.23 percent at the beginning of
1997 to 66 percent at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The city also recorded 45 billion U.S. dollars in imports and
exports, up 15.2 percent over the 1996 figure. International
shipping increased 143.56 percent. Electro-mechanical equipment
continued to dominate the city's exports, accounting for 56.7
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the south China city obtained revenues of
14.4 billion yuan (1.8 billion U.S. dollars), 28 percent more than
1996. Retail sales were up 9.3 percent and the consumer price
index rose by 3 percent. The per-capita GDP was 3,692
U.S. dollars, ranking first in the country, according to the
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
