<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helping Deaf-Mute Children Escape Limits of Silent World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to extensive
rehabilitation, eight-year-old Li Mingming, of China's
Heilongjiang province, who has been deaf since birth, can now
attend class and listen to teachers just like other children.
</P>
<P>
The boy is one of 160 deaf-mute children here who have regained
their sense of speach and hearing after a period of training.
</P>
<P>
China has more than a million deaf-mute children aged 14 and
under, many of their problems having been caused by improper
medical treatment. Although many are not completely deaf,
treatment was usually considered unhelpful or useless.
</P>
<P>
The region's deaf-mute rehabilitation center has made a great
effort to develop whatever hearing remains in children with
disabilities by using physiotherapy, magnetotherapy, and other
forms of therapy.
</P>
<P>
Teachers in the center live with six or seven students and form
a big family. They eat, play, and study with the children, giving
them extensive training in listening and speaking at any hour of
the day, one teacher in her 20s explains.
</P>
<P>
Out of a total of 280 deaf-mute children, 57 have been able to
leave the silent world and have begun new lives in local primary
schools, with an average period of convalescence of one and a half
year, more than two years ahead of the state's intended time
frame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Article Stresses Importance of Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading newspaper, today published a front page commentator's
article stressing the importance of unity.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that many important issues wait to be
resolved in 1998 such as reforming state-owned enterprises, the
re-employment of laid-off workers, shifting functions and
streamlining government bodies, and electing new governments and
legislatures across the country.
</P>
<P>
"All these require us to further improve the unity of the whole
Party and people of all ethnic groups across the country,
especially the unity among leading officials at all levels," the
article states.
</P>
<P>
It points out that the most important thing in seeking unity is
to unify people's thinking, adding that the common ideal lies in
building socialism with Chinese characteristics and
comprehensively reinvigorating the country.
</P>
<P>
"We must strictly follow the basic theories, line and policies
of the Party and unswervingly unite around the Party Central
Committee with Jiang Zemin at the core," it states. "Only this
kind of unity could be considered powerful and invincible."
</P>
<P>
The article urges all Party and government officials to put the
interests of the people, Party and country in first place under
all circumstances and to pay close attention to the people's
difficulties, complaints and wishes.
</P>
<P>
It also stresses that the key to achieving all kinds of unity
is the unity among leading officials.
</P>
<P>
The article calls on leading officials at all levels,
especially the first and second, to treasure unity as their lives
and try to set examples.
</P>
<P>
"Unity is strength and will lead to triumph," the article
notes. "As long as we unite together and combine the wisdom and
strength of the whole Party and people of all ethnic groups, no
difficulty could halt our advancing paces," it concludes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
