<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Dhaka Expects Summit to Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has great expectations for the forthcoming three-South
Asian-nation summit, which is scheduled to be held here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The summit, the first of its kind for heads of government of
Bangladesh, India and Pakistan to gather outside the South Asian
Association for Cooperation (SARRC) forum, is largely seen as
another diplomatic success for Hasina, who received Italian Prime
Minister Romano Prodi just a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
Similar to Prodi's visit, the first of an Italian premier to
this South Asian nation, the tripartite meeting will become the
first of its kind to provide opportunities for the three prime
ministers to address the issue of economic cooperation and
partnership development, setting aside political differences and
other disputes, reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a prime ministers' summit, it is a business summit,
the summit has nothing to do with politics," Bangladesh Foreign
Minister Abdus Samad Azad told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his country expects the summit to bring about a
climate of change, to accelerate the pace of economic development
and expand trade among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
"We can't just wait till resolution of political conflicts,
rather we will have to cope with the vibrant changes taking place
in the world," said Yussuf Abdullah Harun, president of the
Federation of Bangladesh Chamber of Commerce and Industry, on a
different occasion.
</P>
<P>
The summit, originally slated for November 23 last year, but
postponed because of "political compulsions" in Islamabad and New
Delhi, was first proposed by Hasina at the SARRC summit in Male,
capital of the Maldives, in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The one-day summit, which will center on cooperation in trade,
joint-venture investment, energy and infrastructure facilities,
will also be attended by business delegations and representatives
of the chambers of commerce from the three countries, with the aim
of achieving close interaction between government and the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral and his Pakistani
counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, will each lead a 30-odd-strong
delegation while Hasina heads a bigger business delegation.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi businessmen hope the business summit to continue as
an annual event with the three capitals serving as the host by
rotation, according to Harun.
</P>
<P>
"How to face the rest of the world in terms of protecting our
interests in areas we have advantages" would be a key question,
Bangladeshi Foreign Secretary Mustafizur Rahman said. "We will
devise ways how to cooperate and in what areas to cooperate."
</P>
<P>
"We need to emerge as a bloc to negotiate in the global market,
" said Harun. "Unless we get together and pull our resources
together, we cannot face the enormous challenges from the West."
</P>
<P>
The tripartite summit may be confined to economic issues only,
but leaders from the three countries will also deal with other
topics on a bilateral basis, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The simultaneous presence of the Indian and Pakistani prime
ministers in the Bangladesh capital provides opportunities for the
three leaders to hold separate discussions on issues in their
respective bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Hasina is expected to have talks with Gujral, who will arrive
here on Wednesday afternoon and leave on Thursday after the
summit, on the trade imbalance between the two countries,
developments in the diplomatic field and possibly, issues
concerning the implementation of the Ganges water sharing treaty
between the two nations and the Chittagong Hill Tracts accord
between the Bangladesh government and tribal rebels, the analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
And with Sharif, Hasina is expected to discuss trade imbalance,
repatriation of stranded Pakistanis in Bangladesh and such issues
as cooperation in regional and international fora, according to
the analysts.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is scheduled to arrive on Thursday morning and pay a
two-day official visit to Dhaka after the summit.
</P>
<P>
Gujral and Sharif are also likely to use the opportunity to
hold bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which will adopt a Dhaka Declaration calling for
more private-sector cooperation in trade, joint ventures,
transport and communications, will make a positive contribution to
strengthening economic ties among the three nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
