<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Parliament to Sit on Regional Crisis Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Parliament is
expected to give priority to discussions on the region's currency
crisis and its impact on the republic's economy Wednesday when it
starts its first session this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Order Paper of the first session of the Ninth
Parliament of Singapore, which was released to the media on
Tuesday, at least four questions will be raised by the ruling
People's Action Party (PAP), opposition and nominated MPs about
the extent to which Singapore is exposed to the current financial
crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Nominated MP Chuang Shaw Peng will ask Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong, who is also chairman of the Monetary Authority of
Singapore, about the extent of additional exposures Singapore
financial institutions have suffered to bad loans made to regional
economies with rapidly falling currency and equity values and
whether such exposures will lead to banking crises similar to
those in Thailand, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
MP Chng Hee Kok wants to know what is the impact of rising
interest rates on the economy.
</P>
<P>
In the previous two rounds of interest hikes toward the end of
last year, major local banks had already raised their prime
lending rates by one percentage point to 7 percent. And a new
round of prime rate hikes is expected in the near future, as the
key three-month interbank interest rate stayed way too high over
the prime rate.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Workers' Party MP Low Thia Khiang will ask the
minister of finance about the actions Singapore can pursue should
the Indonesian government default on repayment of the loans
extended by Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Singapore People's Party chief MP Chiam See Tong will question
whether the crisis will affect the government's Housing Board
upgrading program as promised by the PAP in the general election
in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, who is on an overnight working
visit to Jakarta on Tuesday, will rush back home just in time for
the parliament sitting Wednesday afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
