<HEADLINE> Internet Use Is Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Internet users were estimated
to number 99.96 million at the end of 1997 and the number is
growing, according to a United States industry publication.
</P>
<P>
The California-based Computer Industry Almanac Inc., which
publishes the Internet Industry Almanac, said in a press release
Monday that the U.S. leads the world in Internet use, having 54.68
million users and a 54.70 percent share of the world Internet
market at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
But as more and more people enjoyed the benefits brought to
them by the new technology, smaller industrialized countries with
the largest number of Internet users were expected to be replaced
by the most populous countries such as China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Almanac, to be released in February, predicts that the
U.S. share of world Internet market will dip to 40 percent by the
end of 2000 as more and more countries adopt Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. share was about 80 percent in 1981 and 65 percent in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Other countries with more than one million Internet users are
Japan, Britain, Canada, Germany, Australia, the Netherlands,
Sweden, Finland and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
