<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Djukanovic in Montenegro Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States will firmly
stand by newly-elected President Milo Djukanovic in the present
political crisis in Montenegro, said a U.S. envoy for former
Yugoslavia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gelbard announced this after separate meetings with
Djukanovic and Montenegro's outgoing President Momir Bulatovic in
the Montenegrin capital Podgorica, Belgrade-based Evening News
reported.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard stressed that his visit to Montenegro indicated
Washington's firm support for Djukanovic's election in the
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
Gelbard warned Bulatovic, who is stepping down on January 15,
that he would risk serious mistakes should he go against the
public will expressed in the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic, the incumbent prime minister of Montenegro, beat
Bulatovic in the second round of the presidential elections on
October 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Despite recognitions of the election results by Western
countries, Bulatovic and his supporters refused to accept the
results. They charged Djukanovic with malpractice in the
elections, and have been calling protests against Djukanovic since.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, tens of thousands of demonstrators gathered in front
of the Assembly Hall protesting against the result of the
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
