<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Proposals on Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday welcomed proposals mapped out by Britain and Ireland on
achieving a peaceful settlement on the dispute over the British
province of Northern Ireland, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
"The president welcomed the initiative of the Irish and British
governments to present 'Propositions for Heads of Agreement' aimed
at moving the Northern Ireland peace talks process forward," the
White House said in a two-sentence statement.
</P>
<P>
"The president encouraged the participants in the talks, who
have the responsibility to shape the substance of a peace
settlement, to seize the moment and begin negotiating details of
an agreement," added the statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, in a document called "Propositions on Heads
of Agreement," governments of Ireland and Britain proposed a new
intergovernmental pact, an elected Northern Ireland assembly and
an all-Ireland ministerial council.
</P>
<P>
The proposals, which politicians from Protestant and Roman
Catholic parties will discuss further Tuesday, also envisage
changes to the Irish republic's constitutional claims over
northern Ireland and to the legislation by which London rules the
province.
</P>
<P>
Since Christmas three people have been shot dead by rival
pro-British and republican guerrilla factions opposed to peace
efforts by British and Irish governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
