<HEADLINE> Boeing, Airbus in Price War for Air India Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Boeing and Airbus have
leashed an all out price war to woo Air India (AI) which is
expected to buy three 200-seater and one 400-seater aircraft in
the near future, local newspaper "The Hindustan Times" said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Even as Air India has called for fresh offers from both global
giants to expedite purchase of four aircraft to meet its expansion
plans, the two rivals have indicated that they would offer amazing
price cuts to win over the national carrier.
</P>
<P>
The contenders for order are Airbus A310-300 with 200 seats and
Boeing B767-200 with 190 seats. Boeing has taken an aggressive
posture by indicating that it would slash its prices by a big
margin to enable Air India to save over 2,000 million rupees
(54.05 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
As compared to the listed price of 80 million dollars for each
B767-200, the company is willing to shave off 15 million dollars
to offer the product to Air India at 65 million dollars per
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the B767-200 would have the capacity to fly
non-stop to London and Tokyo giving the national carrier longer
range as compared to A-310. There is also an accusation that
Airbus was trying to sell a product which is being phased out.
</P>
<P>
While accusing Boeing of trying to hawk a product which has not
been sold to any other airline since 1993, the European consortium
has also indicated its willingness to drop prices to match its
American rival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
