<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Government to Proceed With Peace Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
expressed its determination to proceed with its proposed political
settlement of the ethnic problem even though the main opposition,
the United National Party (UNP), fails to give its support to the
package.
</P>
<P>
Justice, Constitutional Affairs and Ethnic Affairs Minister G.
L. Peiris said Monday that the People's Alliance (PA) government
is determined to hold a non-binding referendum in case the UNP
does not put forward its proposals by the end of this month, the
Daily News newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation of the UNP is essential for the PA to ensure a
two-thirds majority in the parliament, which is mandatory for the
peace proposals to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the referendum will be held under Article 86
of the Sri Lankan Constitution, which empowers the president to
place before the people any question of national importance.
</P>
<P>
The PA government has been trying to win support from the UNP
ever since the peace package was submitted to the parliament for
consideration in 1995.  
</P>
