<HEADLINE> Top Women Breaststrokers to Face off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Penny Heyns and Samantha Riley,
hailed as the best-ever women breastrokers in the world, are to
square off at the 100m final of the World Swimming Championships
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Australian Riley, who swam the year's world best time of one
minute 7.81 seconds in Australia's World Championship trials last
year, won the 100m heats with a time of 1:08.58, just 0.08 seconds
clear of South African Heyns, world record holder and dual Olympic
champion in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
European champion Agnes Kovacs of Hungary came third in the
heats by clocking 1:08.69.
</P>
<P>
Rivalry between Riley and Heyns is deep.
</P>
<P>
In the Atlanta Olympic Games, Henys denied Riley the gold medal
after she shattered the Australian's world mark in the heats.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1997 was for Riley, who beat Heyns in the Pan
Pacific Championships and won the Australian trials in the year's
best time.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's Olympic champion Claudia Poll cruised into the
women's 200m freestyle final after winning the heats in 1:59.82.
</P>
<P>
Poll is expected to win this title since world No.1 swimmer
Chen Yan of China skipped the event to concentrate on individual
medley instead.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Kerstin Kielgass, who beat world record holder and
Olympic silver medalist Franziska van Almisick in the German
trials last year, finished second in 2:00.07, with Australian
Julia Greville third in 2:00.13.
</P>
<P>
European champion Marcel Wouda of the Netherlands won the men's
400m individual medley heats in 4:17.91, 2.53 seconds outside of
the time of 4:15.38 which got him the world No.1 ranking last year.
</P>
<P>
Curtis Myden of Canada finished second with Olympic champion
Tom Dolan of the United States third.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 4x200m freestyle relay heats, the Australian
foursome -- Daniel Kowalski, Grant Hackett, Ian Thoppe and Anthony
Rogis -- timed 7:18.66 to finish first.
</P>
<P>
The United States came second in 7:20.48, 2:39 seconds faster
than Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
