<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Deploy More Security Personnel in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is to
deploy 6,000 more police and military personnel in Jaffna next
week to disarm the armed political groups and to man the January
29 local government elections in the north, security sources here
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Additional police personnel will be deployed in islands around
the Jaffna peninsula where armed members of the Eelam People's
Democratic Party (EDPD), a key Tamil political party contesting
the polls, are present, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
These members were allowed to carry arms because they were
cooperating with the government forces in fighting against the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
However, other political parties participating in the
forthcoming elections have repeatedly protested against the EDPD,
saying free and fair elections could not be held if the EDPD were
allowed to carry arms.
</P>
<P>
EDPD leader Douglas Devananda in response said he would disarm
his members if the government can provide additional security to
the islands where his party members had been protecting civilians
from the LTTE.  
</P>
</TEXT>
