<HEADLINE> Romania Expects Zero Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government will
try to curb the trend of economic decline and achieve a zero
growth this year, Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the economic prospects in 1998, Ciorbea said the
gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to continue dropping in
the first half of this year, but will start to rise in the latter
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
He said strict control on financial deficits and inflation, and
a continued increase of foreign exchange reserves would be the top
priorities of the government in the new year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said financial deficits would be controlled
within 4.2 percent of the GDP, and the inflation rate limited to
30-40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Financial authorities said financial deficits in 1997 accounted
for 4.5 percent of the GDP, while the inflation rate was as high
as 151.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea said the government will step up efforts to reform the
industrial and agricultural sectors as well as financial
institutions. It had also planned to privatize 1,500 to 1,600
state-owned businesses among the total 4,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
