<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Optimistic About Indonesia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Deputy Treasury
Secretary of the United States Lawrence Summers said Monday night
that he remained optimistic about Indonesia's economy.
</P>
<P>
Summers made the statement after a three-hour meeting with
Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad, local press reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Summers, who arrived here on Monday, said his visit to
Indonesia was to perform a special mission for President Bill
Clinton during his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said he would meet Indonesian President Soeharto Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to carrying President Clinton's message to
President Soeharto tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
Summers said earlier that he would expand his Asian tour and
visit Hong Kong, Beijing and Seoul to help boost confidence in the
crisis-ridden region.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Indonesia, Summers will hold several
meetings with Coordinating Minister for Production and
Distribution Hartarto, Minister of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad and
Minister of Industry and Trade Tunky Ariwibowo.
</P>
<P>
Some industrialized countries, including the U.S., Japan,
Germany and Australia, have expressed their concern about the
monetary crisis in Indonesia in recent days. The Indonesian rupiah
declined to a record low of 11,000 per U.S. dollar last Thursday.
The currency has fallen more than 200 percent since July last
year.
</P>
<P>
The drastic fall of rupiah has slowed down the country's
economic activities and threatened businesses with closure and
mass layoff.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) agreed to provide 23 billion U.S. dollars in financial
and technical loans to Indonesia to help overcome its crisis and
Indonesia made a commitment to conduct economic and financial
reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF was reportedly dissatisfied over the process
of the reforms in Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
