<HEADLINE> El Nino to Bring Dry-Season Drought to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Meteorological Department
of Thailand has warned people living outside irrigated zones in
the country to prepare for dry-season droughts caused by the El
Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The department has urged people not to waste water, the local
press reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's lower north, northeast, upper central region and
east will be more seriously affected than other parts due to a
lack of irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, a flow of unusually warm water into the eastern
Pacific, takes place every four or five years and lasts 12 to 18
months. It began in May 1997 and has resulted in unusual weather
patterns in many countries, including Thailand.
</P>
<P>
It reduced rainfall across Thailand, especially in the upper
north, last year.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the volume of water in many reservoirs is low and
there will be a shortage of water between January and May. The
temperature during this period will also be higher than usual, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
Chakkraphan Yomchinda, spokesman of the Thai Interior Ministry,
said on Monday that the ministry has ordered all provinces and
concerned agencies to get personnel, equipment and water trucks
ready to help those affected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
