<HEADLINE> Colombia Suffers Oil Loss Due to Guerrilla Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 200,000 barrels
of oil were spilled in 1997 during the 65 attacks perpetrated by
Colombian guerrillas against the Cano Limon-Covenas oil pipeline,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Attacks were committed by the National Liberation Army and the
Armed Revolutionary Forces of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Both organizations increased their attacks last year against
the infrastructure of the country, specially in oil and power
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The 780-kilometer Cano Limon-Covenas pipeline carries oil from
Piedemonte Llanero, the largest oil field of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline had suffered an annual average of 40 attacks
between 1986 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Apart from economic and ecologic costs of oil spills over
several rivers, production suspension has caused a loss of 5.34
million barrels in these attacks.
</P>
<P>
The figure means some 85 million dollars of exports were
averted, added to repairs and environmental cleaning which costed
13.4 million dollars, the government said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
