<HEADLINE> Philippines Set to Allow Duty-Free Corn Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
allow duty-free imports of yellow corn to enable poultry producers
to cut costs and export their surplus chicken to Hong Kong, local
newspaper the Business Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary Cesar Bautista was quoted as saying Monday that
his department has agreed to do away with tariffs on feed corn
imports used by local poultry firms to make them more competitive.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the Philippines would offer itself as a major
source of dressed chicken to Hong Kong which was recently hit by
the "bird flu" disease.
</P>
<P>
Local poultry producers said earlier that they could not
compete with other countries due to high production costs.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines imposes tariffs ranging from 35 percent to 80
percent on yellow corn imports. Certain quotas are allowed at a
minimum 35 percent but the rest has to be imported at higher
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Trade officials and representatives of the country's poultry
industry will go to Hong Kong this week to check the prospects of
supplying frozen chicken to the city, according to Bautista.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong slaughtered about 1.4 million chickens earlier this
month to minimize the risk of the virus which is transmitted to
humans through direct contact with live birds.  
</P>
