<HEADLINE> China's Largest Port Handles More Containers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Port, China's
largest, handled 2.52 million TEUs of international containers in
1997, 550,000 TEUs more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a rise of 27.9 percent over 1996 and
makes the port eye-catching for increasing its container handling
volume over 26 percent for eight years running.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's fast-growing economy and its role as China's largest
commercial and manufacturing center have contributed to the port's
drastic expansion. Currently, the port handles one quarter of the
country's international cargo shipping and a third of the
country's container shipping, according to port officials.
</P>
<P>
To build Shanghai into an international shipping center, the
port has invested heavily in construction of container berths,
stacking yards and roads, said port officials.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has 19 shipping routes for international
containers and has set up business links with all of the world's
top 25 shipping companies.  
</P>
