<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Up In China's First Special Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, January 13 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's first
special economic zone in southern Guangdong Province, reported 45
billion U.S. dollars in imports and exports in 1997, up 15.2
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The volume accounted for 15 percent of the national total,
ranking first for the fifth consecutive year among the country's
big cities, according to local statistics.
</P>
<P>
The zone's achievements were attributed to a solid foundation
of export-oriented economy, laid over the past 17 years since the
zone was established.
</P>
<P>
The city now boasts China's largest export base for computers,
clocks and watches, and electronic audiovisual products. Some of
its enterprise groups are fairly competitive in the world market.
</P>
</TEXT>
