<HEADLINE> Trade Between Colombia and Andean Countries Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Trade between
Colombia and partner countries of the Andean Community reached 6
billion dollars 1997, Foreign Commerce Minister Carlos Ronderos
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said this year the Andean Community will be strengthened,
and he noted that currently there is "plenty of unity" between
Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela, members of the
trading bloc.
</P>
<P>
The official said that trade between Colombia and Venezuela was
rampant over 1997 with Colombian exports reaching non-precedented
1 billion dollars while Venezuelan sales hit 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade with Peru amounted to 1 billion dollars and with Ecuador
the figure was similar, he added.
</P>
<P>
With Chile, the bilateral Free Trade Agreement was enhanced
last year.
</P>
<P>
The minister announced that the project to join the Andean
Community to the Southern Common Market (Argentina, Brazil,
Uruguay and Paraguay) is about to be discussed next month at a
political and economic meeting. 
