<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Proficiency Test Attracts More Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 foreigners from
around the world took this year's first official Chinese
proficiency test yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The test, also known as "Hanyu Shuiping Kaoshi" (HSK), is the
only state-authorized test to evaluate the proficiency of foreigners
in China and about 60,000 from 120 countries have passed the test
since it was initiated in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that according to a regulation
issued by the State Education Commission (SEC) in 1995, foreign
students have to pass the HSK test when they seek admission to
universities in China.
</P>
<P>
The certificates are also a must for many foreigners when they
seek jobs requiring some fluency in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners can take any of the threes tests, scheduled for
January, May and July. The results come out in about two months.
</P>
<P>
The English newspaper said the majority of those who have
passed the test come from Japan and Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Candidates have included students, diplomats and employees of
foreign companies doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has set up 18 examination centers across the
country while the number of its overseas centers has increased to
16 this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
