<HEADLINE> Ten Soccer Dignities Named for Hall of Champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The soccer's world governing body
named ten greatest retired players for the FIFA Hall of Champions
in the suburb of Paris on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 10 retired players were honoured "for sporting success that
contributed to the positive image of the game".
</P>
<P>
They are Bobby Charlton of England, Stanley Matthews of
England, Pele of Brazil, Franz Beckenbauer of West Germany, Johan
Cruyff of the Netherlands, Alfredo di Stefano of Argentina,
Eusebio of Portugal, Michel Platini of France, Ferenc Puskas of
Hungary and Lev Yashin of former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Former Manchester United manager Matt Busby and Dutchman Rinus
Michels, best known as the man who invented Total Football with
Ajax in the 1970s, were the two managers honoured.
</P>
<P>
Six-time European Cup winners Real Madrid won the club
nomination, with four-time World Cup winners Brazil honoured in
the country category.
</P>
<P>
FIFA said that it will annunally introduce five players to the
Hall of Champions as each of them has an international career of
more than 10 years and retired at least five years ago. 
</P>
