<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher as Stocks Shake Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against
the Japanese yen and German mark Monday as U.S. stocks advanced
despite a selloff in overseas, especially in Hong Kong stocks.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's gains encouraged traders to seek the dollar as a
haven from Asia's troubled financial markets. But lingering fears
that U.S. and Japanese central banks might move in concert to
support the sagging yen limited the dollar's rise.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 132.69 yen,
up from 132.03 late Friday. The U.S. currency also was changing
hands at 1.8211 marks, up from 1.8204.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency has gained about 12 percent against the yen
since the beginning of 1997 amid Asia's economic crisis, reaching
a more than 5-year high of 133.78 on January 5.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4764 Swiss francs, down from 1.4777; 6.0969 French francs, down
from 6.0980; 1,791 Italian lire, up from 1,790; and 1.4341 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.4292.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6215 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6134 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
