<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Avoid Plunging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average avoided today an early 137-point slide triggered by
another rocky day in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Dow changed course three times during the session, rising
66.76 points to 7,647.18, despite falling to its lowest level in
two months during the opening slide.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-7 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where column was heavy at 692.90 million
shares, down slightly from Friday's 746.42 million, the fourth
biggest tally in NYSE history.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 11.52 to 939.21 after
wiping out an early 15-point deficit, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 4.37 to 1,507.59 after recovering from an early
36-point slide.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 4.14 to 491.61, but the
small-company dominated American Stock Exchange composite index
fell 3.83 to 646.41.
</P>
<P>
Technology shares, which are considered especially vulnerable
to the economic trouble in Asia, were instrumental in the
turnaround. Intel, which is due to report on its latest results
after Tuesday's close, rose sharply to lead the rebound on the
technology-heavy Nasdaq market, which briefly fell to its lowest
level since the October selloff.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's main stock index sank 8.7 percent today. Share
prices also fell in Singapore, Japan, Taiwan, Malaysia and
Australia, but rose in two of the region's most troubled nations:
Indonesia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
European markets were pulled lower, too, but some recovered
partially after Wall Street's turnaround.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
