<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Emphasizes Cooperation, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said today that the world body faces the challenge of
reviving the political will for international cooperation and
development.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the ceremonial handover of the
chairmanship of the Group of 77.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Foreign Minister Ali Alatas formally took over the
annual post for 1998 from Tazania's Foreign Minister Jakaya M.
Kikwete.
</P>
<P>
Annan said his reform programs, which will enhance U.N.
effectiveness in the field of development, could not be made
possible without the steadfast cooperation and strong support of
the Group of 77.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77 and the U.N. "walk side by side" and "share the
common understanding" of promoting development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the progress of U.N. reforms, Annan mentioned the
establishment of a new office for development financing, the
freed-up resources to create a "development dividend" and the
greater opportunity for U. N. Conference on Trade and Development
to contribute to deliberations at U.N. Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly' (G.A.)s 52nd session successfully
launched an intergovernmental dialogue on development financing
and the G.A.'s Second Committee reaffirmed a proposal for renewing
the dialogue on international cooperation for development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The recent turmoil in financial markets has demonstrated "the
need for effective multilateralism and a strong United Nations,"
the U.N. chief added.
</P>
<P>
Created on June 15, 1964 and linked with the U.N. system, the
Group of 77 is the world's largest single grouping of developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
