<HEADLINE> Jordan, France to Complement Peace-Saving Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine and Jordan's top leaders reached a consensus here
Monday to complement international efforts to save the stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at a joint press conference by Vedrine and
his Jordanian counterpart Fayez Tarawneh following their meeting
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The French minister, who arrived here earlier from Beirut as
part of his Middle East tour, had also held separate talks with
King Hussein, Crown Prince Hassan and Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said he did not bring a French initiative, but France
would rather work together with all the European Union countries
and the international community, especially the U.S., to remove
the obstacles to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said France is committed to working with other countries to
find a comprehensive, just and lasting peace for the region, and
it appreciates the efforts made by King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Both Vedrine and Tarawneh described the French minister's visit
to Jordan as useful, positive and productive.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Vedrine signed an agreement with the
Jordanian side to grant the kingdom 80 million French francs
(about 13.6 million U.S. dollars) in financial aid.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian side praised France's efforts in alleviating the
sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Majali said there is great prospect for further
cooperation between Jordan and France in all fields, particularly
in investment and economic areas.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine left here for Syria soon after the press conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
