<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has reached an agreement with Sudan to export
to its southern neighbor 5 million U.S. dollars worth of steel,
the Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some European Union countries has ordered goods at
a value of 58.82 million dollars at the Egyptian Iron and Steel
Factory at Helwan, south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has exported altogether 29.41 million dollars worth of
steel during the past six months.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Egyptian ship carrying margarine and soap arrived
in Iraq Monday under the oil-for-food deal between Iraq and the
United Nations, according MENA.
</P>
<P>
The consignment, including 3,000 tonnes of margarine and 2,000
tonnes of soap, involved half of the amount stipulated in an
agreement signed between the Iraqi Ministry of Trade and the
Egyptian Holding Company for Foodstuff Industries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will soon reach agreements on other deal.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion dollars
worth of oil in every six months to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Between 3,500 and 4,000 jobs in Lebanon's gold and
jewelry industry are in danger, the local newspaper Beirut Times
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A reduction of custom duties of 2 percent on imported gold
products and the lower wages of foreign workers will lead to the
layoff of Lebanese workers, said Boghos Kurdian, head of the
Syndicate of Master Goldsmiths and Jewelers.
</P>
<P>
He added that many business owners have employed foreign
workers, mainly from Thailand, because they get much lower pay
than Lebanese workers.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to intervene by putting an
immediate end to the rising number of foreign workers and
consider protective measures.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- British Petroleum, the world's third largest oil
company, has started business in Lebanon, the local newspaper
Daily Star reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, the company's subordinate Air BP for
aircraft fuel bought the Lebanese Aviation Technical Services,
which owns 20 percent of the shares of a fuel depot that was
opened last November at Beirut Airport, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
