<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Iraq should not Choose U.N. Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
on Monday that Iraq had no right to pick and choose U.N. weapons
inspectors to carry out their job of dismantling weapons of mass
destruction in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein shouldn't be able to pick and choose who does
this work," Clinton told reporters at the White House. "If they
are denied their right to do their job tomorrow then I expect the
United Nations Security Council to take strong and appropriate
action."
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Iraq announced through its news agency INA
that it decided to halt the work of the inspection team headed by
American Scott Ritter and has withdrawn permission for him to
undertake any activities inside the Iraq until the composition of
the team has balanced participation from the permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has previously accused Ritter of spying for the United
States. But Ritter has denied the charge, saying the allegation
was "absolutely untrue."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iraqi's U.N. ambassador Nizar Hamdoon said the team,
led by Ritter, was composed of nine American nationals, five
British nationals, one Russian and one Australian, which he said
was "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said the United States had nothing to do with the
composition of ritter's team.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an official of the U.S. National Security Council said
that Iraq's complaints about the balance of team members were
"spurious and irrelevant," and said Iraq could not "pick and
choose" who will inspect its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The official also said Ritter "is not a spy. He is a
professional member of the UNSCOM team. He has inspected Iraq
before. He is not a representative of the United States."
</P>
<P>
The official expected the U.N. Security Council to review the
event and "make clear that Iraq must reverse its position."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
