<DOCNO> XIE19980113.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches Project to Put Schools on the Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- UK Netyear, a project destined
to connect the country's every school to the Internet, begins
today.
</P>
<P>
The launch ceremony, held simultaneously in London, Belfast,
Cardiff and Glasgow, includes the linking of a total of 23 schools
across the UK through videoconferencing.
</P>
<P>
Only 6,000 schools in the UK are currently connected to the
Internet. The aim of Netyear is to increase this to 17,000 by the
end of 1998, and 32,000 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Under the ambitious scheme, basic training in the use of the
Internet will be provided free of charge on a CD-ROM to every
school that registers with the new project.
</P>
<P>
Free email for all pupils and teachers will be a key feature of
the scheme, it was announced.
</P>
<P>
Every school in the country will be urged to register, free of
charge and they will be given help to raise money to provide
computer equipment to get them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Founders of the project are Cisco Systems, ICL, The Daily
Telegraph and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
The four companies have underwritten a budget of about two
million pounds (3.2 million U.S. dollars) to help train teachers
and students to use the Internet for teaching and learning.
</P>
<P>
UK Netyear is part of the British government's wider plan of
National Grid for Learning, which ultimately aims to connect
schools, libraries, museums and other organizations together via
the Internet by the year 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
